column85: Cont1 Valve Or Device Fail Ind
column168: Description Of Events

ONE CARTON OF 2 GLASS LITER BOTTLES OF METHANOL WAS LEAKING WHEN TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED UPON ARRIVAL INTO PENSACOLA.  LEAKING CASE WAS PUT IN RECOVERY CONTAINER WITH DRY ABSORBANT.  THE BROKEN LITER WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH ONE GALLON OF CLOROX.

A 5 GALLON PAIL FELL OFF THE PALLET IN TRANSIT TO CUSTOMERS DOCK.  PAIL LEAKED AT THE LID.  LOST APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS. ALSO SPILLED ON 1 BOX OF 4 GALLONS SATURATING THAT BOX. CUSTOMER REFUSED THAT TOO.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: AS VAC BOX TRUCK WAS TURNING INTO THE DISPOSAL FACILITY, IT HIT A BUMP, THUS JARRING THE LOAD AND PLACING STRESS ON THE GASKET AROUND THE BACK ENCLOSURE CAUSING IT TO FAIL.  APPROXIMATELY 25 POUNDS OF MATERIAL WAS SPILLED AT THE ENTRANCE OF THE FACILITY. ALL OF THE MATERIAL WAS SWEPT UP, AND PLACED BACK INTO THE VAC BOX FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF THIS MATERIAL LEAKING FROM A CONTAINER IN THE OF THE TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED AT SAPP BROTHERS TRUCK STOP IN OMAHA, NE.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  A LOCAL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR WAS EMPLOYED.  THEIR CREW CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND OVERPACKED THE CONTAINER.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: DRIVER HAVING PROBLEM WITH INTERNAL VALVE.  COULDN'T GE IT OPENED ENOUGH. WHILE HE WAS WORKING ON IT, HE LOST PRODUCT FROM THE HOSE.  CUSTOMER CLEANED UP.

SKID WAS IMBEDDED IN ANOTHER SKID.  USED FORKLIFT TO REMOVE SKID.  FORK PUNCTURED CARTON CAUSING LEAK.  PRODUCT ABSORBED WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL. PRODUCT RECOOPED AND CONSIGNEE NOTIFIED; AND GAVE AUTHORIZATION TO DELIVER FREIGHT.

AS THIS TRAILER WAS MOVING FROM ORIGIN TERMINAL TO DESTINATION TERMINAL, THE DRIVER NOTICED SOME FLUID ON THE BACK END OF THE TRAILER.  UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOOR IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 2 DRUMS HAD FALLEN OFF OF THE PALLET AND HAD BURST OPEN.  THE PRODUCT WAS A DILUTED CORROSIVE.  WE APPLIED ABSORBANT TO THE SPILL AND CONTAINED THE LEAK.  ONCE THE ABSORBANT NEUTRALIZED THE CORROSIVE WE DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  THE 2 DRUMS WERE ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

DRIVER DISCOVERED BRAKE FLUID LEAKING AT REST AREA.  UPON INSPECTION OF TRAILER CONTENTS HE FOUND ONE TOTE TANK WITH A CRACK IN A SEAM OF THE TANK.  THE TANK APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED ONLY WHEN THE PRODUCT "SLOSHED" UP TO THE HEIGHT OF THE CRACK.  REPAIR PUTTY WAS PLACED ON THE CRACK AND ABSORBENT WAS USED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  AKK WASTE & PRODUCT WAS ACCEPTED AT THE RECEIVER.

PARCEL WAS DISCOVERED ON THE TELLOW BELT.  ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE IN TUB. ENTIRE BOX WET WITH THE CORROSIVE LIQUID-CLEANING COMPOUND.  1 OF 12 QUARTS HAD A DEFECTIVE LID, THE LID WAS PUSHED INWARD CAUSING LEAKAGE OF ENTIRE QUART.  THE DAMAGED MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING DOT SPECIFICATIONS.  AN ISP CARD WAS WRITTEN TO THE ORIGIN DISTRICT FOR FOLLOW UP WITH SHIPPER TO CORRECT FUTURE SHIPMENTS.

column168: PARCEL WAS FOUND LEAKING IN THE UNLOAD.  THE CAPS ON THE BOTTLES WERE LOOSE.  THE CAPS WERE RETIGHTENED AND PACKAGED IN A NEW BOX AND THE ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE LABELED FOR SHIPPING.  THE CONTAMINATED PACKING MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

THE BAGS WERE TAPED TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKING THEN SHRINK WRAPPED ALONG WITH THE PLASTIC PAIL ON ONE PALLET AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER AUTHORITY OF STEVE MILDREW WITH INDSPEC ON PRO 922-169706.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: ONE DRUM DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING A ROUTINE SAFETY CHECK.  THE TOP OF ONE DRUM HAD MOISTURE ON TOP FROM A LEAKING BUNG.  DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN BUT THE THREADS WERE STRIPPED.  DRIVER PUT SEALANT ON THE THREADS TO STOP THE LEAK.  ALL PRODUCT ACCEPTED AT THE RECEIVER.
IT APPEARS THAT THE WEIGHT OF OTHER FREIGHT CAUSED THE NECK OF THE ONE GALLON JUG TO BEND.  THE RESULTING CREASE IN THE PLASTIC DEVELOP A TINY LEAK ALLOWING A FEW DROPS OF SOLUTION TO ESCAPE.
column172: Plastic jug, capacity more than 2 gallons and less than 5 gallons

column168: DRUM WAS DISCOVERED WITH A LOOSE BUNG WHILE UNLOADING.  BUNG WAS TIGHTENED AND DRUM WAS FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.  TWO GALLONS SPILLED EVAPORATED.
THE TANK WENT EMPTY, AND DRIVER BLEEDING PRESSURE OFF LINE INTO A BUCKET. THERE WAS SOMETHING IN THE VALVE AND WHEN IT HIT THE BUCKET SOME PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT, WIPED IT UP WITH PAPER TOWELS.
THE WING NUT ON THE SHUT OFF VALVE WAS LOOSE AND WHEN CUSTOMER WENT TO SHUT IT OFF IT LEAKED A LITTLE.  CUSTOMER CLEANED UP WITH DRY SWEEP.
PRODUCT CAME OUT CUSTOMER VENT ON TANK WHEN DRIVER FINISHED UNLOADING. CLEANED UP BY CONSIGNEE.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT 00:40, SWITCHING CREW NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING SLIGHTLY OUT DOME ON CAR. AUTHORITIES NOTIFIED AT 00:45 AND INFORMED YARDMASTER TO PLACE CAR IN ISOLATION.  APPEARED CAR LEAKED ONLY WHEN PLACED IN MOTION AND THEN ONLY SLIGHTLY.  INSPECTION INDICATED THE DOME WAS NOT SECURED.  TEXACO PERSONNEL ARRIVED AT 08:30 HOURS AND ADVISED IN FACT THE DOME WAS LOOSE AND NOT SECURED.  TEXACO PERSONNELL TIGHTENED BOLTS DOWN ON DOME AND CAR APPROVED FOR MOVEMENT BACK INTO INDUSTRY.  NOTE: CAR WAS RELEASED BY TEXACO AS EMPTY ON 9-14-93.  THEY DISCOVERED ON 9-15-93 THAT CAR MIGHT STILL BE LOADED.  CAR IN FACT WAS STILL LOADED AND MOVED BACK TO INDUSTRY AFTER DOME BOLTS TIGHTENED 9-16-93.

AT 02:45 HOURS, 9/12/93, SWITCHING CREW NOTICED LIQUID SPILL OUT TOP OF CAR IN THE VICINITY OF THE DOME ON TOP OF CAR WHEN CAR WAS PLACED IN MOTION AND SWITCHED INTO TRACK.  SPILL APPEARED CONFINED TO TOP OF CAR ONLY.  CAR WAS LEFT IN TRACK UNTIL 09:30 HOURS AT WHICH TIME IT WAS PLACED IN ISOLATION AND INSPECTED BY KCS PERSONNEL.  INSPECTION REVEALED PRODUCT LEAKING OUT PRESSURE RELEIF VENT INDICATING RUPTURED 100 POUND DISK. SHIPPER AND OTHER AUTHORITIES WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED.  OCCIDENTAL PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 09:10 HOURS 9/13/93 AND MADE NECESSARY REPAIRS BY REPLACING THE RUPTURED DISK.  REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED AT 09:25 HOURS AND CAR APPROVED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: THE MANWAY ON TOP OF CARGO TANK WAS IMPROPERLY SECURED AFTER LOADING. APPROXIMATELY 1/2 TO 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL SEEPED INTO SPILL DAM AROUND MANWAY AND A SMALL PORTION RAN DOWN EXTERIOR OF CARGO TANK.  THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS ENTIRELY CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENT PADS AND ALL CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF AT THE CONSIGNEE.  NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ENTERED ANY DRAINS OR WATERWAYS.

ARRIVED MILWAUKEE OFF TRAILER 202072 IN DAMAGED LEAKING CONDITION, CAUSED BY LOADING CARTONS ONTO A FILMSY PALLET AND WHEN THE PALLET WAS TRANSPORTED DURING LOADING OR RELAY THE PALLET SPLIT PUNCTURING THE BOTTOM OF 1 CARTON AND ALSO PUNCTURING 1 GALLON BOTTOLE OF COMPOUND CLEAN UP WITH WATER BOTTLE WAS DUMPED AND CARTON WAS DUMPED THE OTHER 3 BOTTLES IN THE CASE RECOOPERED TO A NEW CARTON FOR DELIVERY TO CONSIGNEE.
THIS SHIPMENT WAS SITTING ON OVER DOCK. DOCKMAN RAN INTO 1 DRUM WITH FORKLIFT AND CRUNCHED THE SIDE, FORCING.  THE TOP OFF AND SOME CONTENTS TO SPILL.  PUT IN RECOVERY DRUM.
PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED WITH LEAKAGE NOTED. EXAMINATION OF THE METAL DRUM REVEALED A RUPTURED SEAM. THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED. PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

PARCEL WAS FOUND ON THE RED WALL.  ONE OF SIX ONE GALLON BOTTLES HAD A LOOSE CAP.  CAPS WERE TIGHTENED AND ALL SIX BOTTLES WERE SENT ON FOR DELIVERY.  CONTAMINATED PACKING MATERIAL AND CORRUGATED CARTON WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED AT PD-9 AT WHICH TIME THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND THE REMAINING MATERIAL WERE DISPOSED OF UNDER THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.  THE CUSTOMER WAS CONTACTED THROUGH THE DAMAGE REPORTING PROCEDURE, AT WHICH TIME A RECOMMENDATION WAS MADE ON PROPER PACKING.

WHILE DOCKMAN UNLOADED DRUM FROM TRAILER, HE PUNCTURED ITS SIDE WITH FORKLIFT.  SPILLING APPROX. 5 GALLONS.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBANT COMPOUND AND THE DRUM WAS PATCHED TO BE SENT ON TO ITS DESTINATION.  PATCH DID NOT HOLD AND DRUM LEAKED AND ADDITIONAL 12 GALLONS ONTO TRAILER WHICH EVAPORTAED NRC WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL AS THE SHIPPER. PRODUCT WAS PLACED INTO A 85 GALLON OVERPACK AND WE ARE WAITING RETURN AUTHORIZATION FROM SHIPPER.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device; Dropped
column168: THE CYLINDER FELL OFF A 2-WHEELER WHILE IT WAS BEING UNLOADED.  THE CYLINDEER STARTED LEAKING AND THEY EVACUATED THE TERMINAL DOCK.  SPILTEECH SERVICE WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT.  THE VALVE STEM WAS FOUND OPEN AND THE VALVE WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF.  MOST OF THE 15 POUNDS OF PRODUCT WAS ESTIMATED TO HAVE REMAINED IN THE CYLINDER.  THE PRODUCT OUTLET CAP WAS FOUND TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  INSPECTION OF THE CAP'S INTERIOR REVEALED THAT THE RUBBER SEAT WHICH SEALS THE CAP TO THE OUTLET HAD BECOME WORN AND WOULD NO LONGER FORM A SEAL.  A REPLACEMENT GASKET WAS INSERTED, AND THE CYLINDER WAS CHECKED FOR LEAKS.  SHIPPER GAVE RETURN AUTHOTIZATION.
column172: Cylindrical metal container, not for compressed gases (i. e., not a pressure vessel)

column168: I WAS CALLED AT APPROX. 1415 HOURS ON SEPTEMBER 10, 1993 TO CHECK LEAKING CAR ON THE HUMP.  I FOUND THE ABOVE CAR LEAKING FROM THE OUTER JACKET AROUND THE BOTTOM OF THE OUTLET VALVE.  CHEMTREC WAS CALLED WHO NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, LYONDELL PETROCHEMICAL. THE CAR WAS OFF LOADED INTO FOUR (4) TRAILERS PULLED BY MATLOCK TRUCKS ON SEPTEMBER 11, 1993 BY O.H. MATERIALS ENVIRONMENTAL CORPORATION, DIRECTED BY BRAIN SESSAMAN OF LYONDELL PETROCHEMICAL COMPANY.  APPROX. 2000 GALLONS IN THE CAR WILL BE OFF LOADED MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 13, 1993, THAT THESE FOUR (4) TRAILERS COULD NOT HOLD. THE CAR WAS NOT LEAKING AFTER FOUR(4) TRUCKS WERE LOADED.  MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 13, 1993 AT 1230 HOURS, ANOTHER MATLOCK TRUCK WAS USED TO OFF LOAD THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS STENCILLED. "LEAKY TANK- DO NOT LOAD.  HOME SHOP TO GENERAL ELECTRIC RAILCAR SHOP, RANGER, TEXAS."  ON APRIL 25, 1992, I HAD THE SAME CAR WITH THE SAME PROBLEM.

THE CONSIGNEE WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION.

APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM, WITH PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED.  THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED, CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  THE SALVAGE DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CLAIM CREDIT. A ROAD DRIVER FOUND HIS TRAILER LEAKING AT THE SCALE OFF OF I-55.  THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  A CERTIFIED EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED AND DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  A STEEL DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING AND WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW D.O.T. APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM, WITH PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED AND DISPOSED OF AT A LICENSED FACILITY.  THE SPILLAGE WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP.  THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON 9/16/93 AT APPROXIMATELY 8:20 A.M. OUR TRUCK #36-94 WAS INVOLVED IN A ROLLOVER INCIDENT ON JAMISON HILL ROAD IN THE TOWN OF STANFORD, DUTCHESS COUNTY.  THE DRIVER, CHARLIE DEBELLIS WAS BACKING UP JAMISON HILL ROAD IN PROPARATION TO MAKE A POUR ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROAD AND HE GOT OFF TO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AND INTO SOME SOFT FILL AND THE TRUCK OVERTURNED ONTO IT'S ROOF.  I WAS CALLED AT 8:30 AND WAS TOLD THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND THAT THERE WAS NO SPILL.  JOE BOYCE RESPONDED AND I ALSO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  JOE HAD ALREADY CONTACTED THE WRECKER (BRYANTS) AND HAD A TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT RESPONDING.  IN ADDITION GARY COOPER RESPONDED FROM THE T/O CLINTON WHERE HE HAD BEEN SEEING A CUSTOMER.  WHEN I ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 THE SCENE AND VECHILE WERE SECURE AND WE BEGAN TO DISCUSS HOW WE WOULD UNLOAD THE TRUCK BEING THAT IT WAS IN AN INVERTED POSITION.  A CALL WAS MADE TO ETNYRE AND THE DECISION WAS  MADE TO EMPTY IT BY USING THE INTERNAL VENT THAT TERMINATED AT A 3" FITTING AT THE BOTTON OF THE TRUCK.  THIS FITTING WAS NOW UPRIGHT BECAUSE OF THE VECHILE POSITION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 10:00 THE UNLOADING OF THE TRUCK BEGAN AND WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT INCIDENT ABOUT 30 MINUTES LATER.  THE PROCESS OF UPRIGHTING THE TRUCK WAS BEGUN AND WAS COMPLETED AT 12:00 NOON.  THE TRUCK SUSTAINED DAMAGE TO THE EXHAUST STACKS THE TANK INSULATION SKIN IS $14,000.  GARY COOPER KNEW AN EXCAVATING CONTRACTOR (DUFFY LAYTON) WHO RESPONDED WITH AN EXCAVATOR AND A TEN WHEEL DUMPTRUCK.  HE IMMEDIATELY BEGAN CLEANUP.  NYSDEC HAD REQUESTED IMMEDIATE CLEANUP OF THE AREA.  THE CLEANUP CONSISTED OF ONE TEN LOAD OF FILL WAS BROUGHT IN AND SPREAD OVER THE AREA TO REPLACE THE SOIL THAT HAD BEEN EXCAVATED.  NYSDEC HAD ASSIGNED A SPILL NUMBER OF 9307328 TO THIS INCIDENT.  DUTCHESS COUNTY HAD ASIGNED RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HAD AN ON SCENE COORDINATOR NAMED KEVIN FOGARTY (914)894-2222. NYS POLICE RESPONDED AND THE HAZMAT COORDINATOR FOR THEM WAS GARY KNAPP OF THE TROOP K MILLBROOK BARRACKS.  NYSDEC (DELORES WAS NOTIFIED AT 5:00P.M. THAT CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED.  SHE INFORMED ME TO FIND A LOCAL CONTRACTOR TO DISPOSE OF THE ASPHALT SOIL VEGETATION MIX. THE FIRE CHEIF FOR THE TWON OF STAMFORD WAS JEFFERY SPIERS 914-868-7466.

A TANK TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM BIOCRAFT LABORATORIES, INC. LOCATED AT 12 INDUSTRIAL AVENUE IN WALDRICK, NJ TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD.  WAITING TO BE OFF-LOADED AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY, THE DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL DRIP COMING FROM THE LEVEL INDICATOR LOCATED ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TANK ONTO THE CEMENT DRIVEWAY OF THE FACILITY. PERSONNEL FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND OFF-LOADED THE MATERIAL INTO AN ON-SITE TANK.  ALL ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINERIZED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER USED TO TRANSPORT THE MATERIAL TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC.  PRIOR TO DISPATCH, THE DRIVER PERFORMED A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION AND DID NOT IDENTIFY ANY DEFICIENCIES WITH THIS UNIT.  IT WAS DISCOVERED AFTER THE VEHICLE WAS OFF-LOADED THAT THE PACKING SEAL ON THE LEVEL INDICATOR THAT PREVENTS PRODUCT FROM ESCAPING FROM THIS GAUGE HAD FAILED.  CLEAN HARBOR'S PERSONNEL INSTALLED A NEW PACKING SEAL AND CORRECTED THIS MECHANICAL FAILURE.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO COMPLETE THE REQUIRED PRE AND POST TRIP INSPECTIONS ON EACH VEHICLE USED AND REPORT ANY DEFICIENCIES TO THE PROPER INDIVIDUAL.  IN ADDITION, ALL DEFICIENCIES FOUND WILL BE IMMEDIATELY CORRECTED EITHER BY CLEAN HARBOR'S MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL OR OUTSIDE REPAIR AGENCIES.

AFTER REPRESENTATIVE SERVICED SHAHEEN CHEVY, REPRESENTATIVE WAS MOVING DRUMS AROUND TO PUT CLEAN MATERIAL TOWARDS THE BACK OF TRUCK AND THE DIRTY MATERIAL TOWARDS THE FRONT FOR EASIER ACCESS, WHILE MOVING DIRTY DRUM OF SOLVENT, THE DRUM SLIPPED OUT OF HIS HAND AND FELL, LID CAME OFF DRUM. ALL MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND DRUMMED, TAGGED AND SENT OUT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: DRIVER HAD TO APPLY BRAKES HARD TO AVOID A CAR THAT HAD PULLED OUT IN FRONT OF HIM.  THE HARD BRAKE APPLICIATION CAUSED DUNNAGE TO FAIL ALLOWING THE CARGO OF 55 GALLON DRUMS TO MOVE FORWARD INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE MOVEMENT OF DRUMS AGAINST THE TRAILER BULKHEAD CAUSED DAMAGE TO THE TOPS OF 16 DRUMS WHICH RESULTED IN THE LIDS NOT SEALING PROPERLY. APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS SPILLED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  NO MATERIAL LEAKED OUTSIDE THE TRAILER DUE TO BEING CONTAINED ON STEEL SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN.  A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO SCENE TO OVERPACK DAMAGED DRUMS AND REPOSITION CARGO.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED AS A COURTESY (REPORT NO. 197045) AS WELL AS THE FLORIDA STATE WARNING POINT, DIVISION OF EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT.  THE FLORIDA HIGHWAY PATROL WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.  SHIPMENT PROCEEDED ON TO DESTINATION WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEM.

WHILE UNLOADING SHORT PALLET (48X40) WITH FORKLIFT, BLADE EXTENCDING OUT UNCTURED FIVE GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER CAUSING SPILL INSIDE CARGO TRAILER. NO DAMAGE OTHER THAN SAID ONE CONTAINER.  INTERNAL CLEAN-UP BY CARRIER AND PROPERLY DISPOSE.

CUSTOMER HAD A FEMALE QUICK COUPLER ATTACHED TO THE RECEIVING LINE IN SUCH A WAY THAT IT ALLOWED PUMP VIBRATIONS TO VIBRATE OPEN ONE OF THE LOCKDOWN EARS, CREATING A LOOSE FIT CONNECTION, WHICH UNDER PRESSURE, ALLOWED FOR A RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  DRIVER HAD NOTED PROBLEM AND HAD SECURED THE EARS RIGHT FROM THE FIRST, BUT THE SECURITY TIE ALSO FAILED.  CLEAN-UP CREW WAS SENT IN TO TAKE CARE OF SPILL-(ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS OF ILLINOIS)

AT APPROXIMATELY 0730 HOURS ON SEPTEMBER 16, 1993 IN FRONTIER YARD, A BRAKEMAN NOTICED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM UTLX 13131 SHORTLY AFTER THE CAR WAS HUMPED.  A TEAM FROM MARSULEX RESPONDED AND REPLACED A RUPTURED DISC.

UPON ARRIVAL AT KENTON YARD, THE ACFX 77792 WAS NOTICED TO HAVE LEAKED AT APPROXIMATELY 12:50 HOURS ON SEPTEMBER 14TH.  OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL RESPONDED AND DISCOVERED A DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET.  THEY REPLACED SAME.

WHILE INSPECTING AN INBOUND TRAIN, A CAR INSPECTOR DISCOVERED TANK CAR UTLX 200333 LEAKING FROM AREA OF THE MANWAY.  CHEMTREC, SHIPPER AND RAILROAD HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER NOTIFIED.  FURTHER INSPECTION DETERMINED A VALVE WAS LOOSE.  AFTER THE VALVE WAS TIGHTNED, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

WHILE INSPECTING ITERMODAL PORTABLE TANK MOLU 936413, CAR INSPECTOR DISCOVERED LEAK AT FLANGEWAY.  CHEMTREC, THE SHIPPER, AND RAILROAD HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDERS WERE NOTIFIED.  FURTHER INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THERE WERE LOOSE BOLTS IN THE BOTTOM END-FLANGE FITTING. AFTER THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED, THE LEAK STOPPED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

A MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEE AT THE DENVER RIP TRACK SMELLED AMMONIA. TANK CAR GATX 89980 ON WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM A LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE. BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR AND RAILROAD RESPONDER TIGHTENED THE NUTS ON THE BOLTS SECURING THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE ON THE B-END OF THE TANK CAR.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

column168: SEABOARD DRIVER WAS SENT TO THE GASOLINE STATION TO PUMP PRODUCT FROM THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK INTO CARRIER CARGO TANK.  THE DRIVER HOOKED UP HOSED AND STARTED PUMPING.  THE PRODUCT WAS TO BE PUMPED INTO THE CARGO TANK THROUGH THE MANIFOLD ON THE CARGO TANK.  THE DRIVER PUMPED AGAINST CLOSED VALVES IN THE MANIFOLD.  THE PRESSURE OF THE PRODUCT BEING PUMPED AGAINST THE CLOSED VALVE CAUSED THE MANIFOLD TO IMMEDIATELY CRACK.  THE GASOLINE RAN OUT OF THE MANIFOLD ONTO THE STATION PAVEMENT AND ONTO THE ROADWAY.  THE FIRE AND POLICE WERE IMMEDIATELY CALLED BY THE DRIVER TO THE SCENE AND THIS COMPANY'S CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS ALSO IMMEDIATELY CALLED TO THE SCENE TO CLEAN UP THE PRODCUT.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: DURING THE AFTERNOON OF SEPTEMBER 27, 1993 AT APPROXIMATELY 3:45pm A FLORIDA POWER (FPC) DRIVER REPORTED THE SPILL OF APPROX. 50 GALLONS OF LIQUICHLOR (SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE 12.5%).  THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTING THE MATERIAL FROM OUR WILDWOOD STORES FACILITY IN WILDWOOD, FLORIDA TO OUR SUWANEE RIVER POWER PLANT.  THE VEHICLE WAS DRIVING ALONG COUNTY ROAD 466, APPROXIMATELY 5 MILES NORTH OF WILDWOOD WHEN THE STEEL SECURING BANDS AROUND THE DRUMS BROKE ALLOWING TWO DRUMS OF THE PRODUCT TO FALL OFF THE TRANSPORT TRAILER.  ONE DRUM OF LIQUICHLOR RUPTURES AND LEAKED PRODUCT ONTO THE ROADSIDE AND TO AN ADJOINING PROPERTY. THE SECOND DRUM REMAINED INTACT AND DID NOT LEAK.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR WHO GOT IN CONTACT WITH THE FPC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES DEPARTMENT.  AFTER REVEIWING THE MSDS FOR THE PRODUCT IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE AMOUNT SPILLED WAS LESS THAN THE RQ FOR THE PRODUCT.  IN ADDITION, IT WAS DTERMINED THAT NONE OF THE DOT CRITERIA REQUIRING IMMEDIATE NOTIFICATION OF THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS MET.  FROM THE MSDS IT WAS DETERMINED THAT FLUSHING THE SPILL WITH LARGE AMOUNTS OF WATER WAS THE RECOMMENDED CLEANUP METHOD. BECAUSE OF AN APPROACHING RAIN, STORM, THE ENTIRE INCIDENT SITE WAS FLUSHED WITH RAIN WATER WITHIN ONE HOUR OF THE LEAK.  THE RUPTURED DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE A SECOND VEHICLE, SECURED AND RETURNED TO WILDWOOD.  THE SECOND, INTACT DRUM, WAS REMOVED FROM THE ROADSIDE, RETURNED TO THE ORIGINAL DELIVERY TRAILER, SECURED AND SENT WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE DELIVERY TO SUWANEE PLANT.  UPON RETURNING TO THE WILDWOOD FACILITY (APPROX. 5:15pm) THE SUPERVISOR CONTACTED THE PROPERTY OWNER AND TOLD HER WHAT HAPPENED, GAVE HER THE NAME OF THE PRODUCT THAT HAD SPILLED ON HER PROPERTY.  SHE WAS ALSO PROVIDED A FPC CONTACT NUMBER INCASE SHE HAS ADDITIONAL QUESTIONS.  FUTURE SHIPMENTS THAT INCLUDE BANDED MATERIALS WILL BE INSPECTED CLOSER BEFORE LEAVING THE STOREROOM.

DRIVER CALLED @ APPROXIMATELY 13:45 IN REGARDS TO A STRONG ODOR.  WHICH APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PAKG. UPON ARRIVAL I ENTERED THE PACKAGE CAR, GOT THE EMERGENCY RESPONDER BOOK AND WENT INTO THE REAR TO INSPECT THE PACKAGES.  I OBSERVED 3 HAZ MAT PKGS ON THE FLOOR ALL FROM THE SAME SHIPPER GOING TO THE SAME CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO VISABLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE, A VERY STONG ODOR.  I CHECKED THE UN NUMBER ON THE SUSPECT PACKAGE, REFERRED TO THE REPONDER BOOK AND DETERMINED A RESPONSE WAS NECESSARY.  I CALLED THE CENTER AND ADVISED THEM TO NOTIFY A RESPONSE TEAM AND RECOMMEND THE DRIVER BE TRANSPORTED FOR MEDICAL TREATMENT.  UPON THE ARRIVAL OF THE RESPONSE TEAM, CHIEF OHISHEM OF HYANNIS FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS IN COMMAND OVER THE PACKAGE AND SECURED IT.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT BAD PACKAGING CAUSED THE LEAK AND A VISIT WILL BE MADE TO THE SHIPPER TO HELP HIM IMPROVE PACKAGING.

column168: DURING THE ROUTINE LOADING OF A SHIPMENT OF PCB TRANSFORMERS, ONE OF THE TOPS OF ONE OF THE TRANSFORMERS WAS DAMAGED, I.E., THE ELECTRODE WAS DAMAGED.  UPON PLACEMENT OF THE TRANSFORMER ON THE FLATBED TRAILER, THE TRANSFORMER WAS MOVED IN A MANNER WHICH CAUSED SOME FLUID TO SPLASH THROUGH THE OPENING.  THE TRANSFORMER HAD A CAPACITY OF 25 GALLONS.  THE FLUID CONTAINED 202 PARTS PER MILLION OF POLYCHLORINATED BIPHENYLS.  SOME OF THE FLUID RAN DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TRANSFORMER ITSELF.  THE BED OF THE TRAILER, WHICH WAS MADE OF METAL, AND THE METAL SIDE CONTAINMENT RAIL WERE ALSO CONTAMINATED BY THE FLUID.  THE TOTAL VOLUME OF FLUID DISCHARGED WAS ESTIMATED TO BE FOUR FLUID OUNCES.  THE EMPLOYEES LOADING THE TRANSFORMER CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY COORDINATOR.  THE SPILL WAS ASSESSED, IT WAS NOT NECESSARY TO IMPLEMENT THE CONTINGENCY PLAN.  THE EMPLOYEES WERE INSTRUCTED IN THE PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (POLYTYVEK BODY COVERING AND SHOE COVERING, N-DEX INNER GLOVES, NITRIL OUTER GLOVES, FULLFACE RESPIRATOR WITH ORGANIC VAPOR AND HEPA CARTRIDGE), THE PHYSICAL AND CHEMICAL PROPERTIES OF THE RELEASED MATERIAL, AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH TSCA, THE MANNER IN WHICH THE SPILL MUST BE ADDRESSED.  THE PCB CONTAMINATED AREAS WERE DECONTAMINATED (DOUBLE WASHING) USING HEXANE AS THE SOLVENT.  THE SOLVENT WAS ABSORBED USING TOWELING.  ALL CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT MATERIAL, SOLVENT, AND PPE WERE PLACED INTO THE PCB LABORATORY SATELLITE ACCUMULATION CONTAINER.  THIS CONTAINER IS USED TO MANAGE PCB WASTES GENERATED BY THE LABORATORY, INCLUDING PPE AND WIPES.  UPON FILLING OF THE CONTAINER IT IS PLACED INTO STORAGE ON THE PCB STORAGE PAD AND ULTIMATELY DISPOSED IN ACCORDANCE WITH TSCA REGULATIONS.

A LOAD OF HIGH SULFUR #2 FUEL OIL WAS ORDERED BY FILTER OIL. THE PRODUCT WAS TO BE DELIVERED TO THEIR BULK STORAGE FACILITY, TANK #7, AT N51 W5358 PORTLAND ROAD, CEDARBURG WI53012. THE ORDER WAS DISPATCHED FOR THE FACILITY INTO TANK #6 IN ERROR.  THE TRANSPORT DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY AT 10:00 P.M. AND MADE HIS CONNECTIONS TO THE NECESSARY PIPING. HE THEN TRACED THE PIPING TO TANK 36 AND OPENED THE APPROPRIATE VALVES. THE VALVES AND TANK WERE MARKED #1 FUEL OIL BUT THE DRIVER DID NOT CATCH THE MARKINGS. THE DRIVER NOTICED THE TANK WAS VISIBLY SMALLER THAN THE SURROUNDING TANKS. AFTER OBTAINING TANK READINGS AND FINDING THE TANK EMPTY AND CONFIRMING THE TANK #6, EVERYTHING WAS SECURE. HE TRANSFERRED APPROXIMATELY 6000 GALLONS OF HIS 7500 GALLON LOAD AND AGAIN CHECKED THE PIPING FOR LEAKS. AT THIS TIME HE DISCOVERED STANDING PRODUCT CONTAINED WITHIN THE CONTAINMENT DIKE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CEASED TRANSFER OPERATIONS AND FOLLOWED JJ TRANSPORT, INC PROTOCOL FOR NOTIFICATION. THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES WERE NOTIFED AND RESPONDED. JJ TRANSPORT, INC., GREAT WEST CASUALTY, CEDARBURG FIRE DEPARTMENT, OZAUKEE COUNTY EMERGENCY GOVERNMENT, WISCONSIN DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES. IT WAS LATER DISCOVERED THAT TANK #6 HAD A CAPACITY OF 3136 GALLONS. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RETRIEVED APPROXIMATELY 1925 GALLONS OF STANDING PRODUCT FROM THE CONTAIMENT DIKE. FURTHER SITE ASSESSMENT  AND CLEAN-UP IS ONGOING AND NO OTHER INFORMATION IS AVAILABLE AT THIS TIME.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: I AM WRITING IN REGARD TO THE INCIDENT THAT OCCURRED ON SEPT. 13,1993 ON RT 322 JUST OUTSIDE OF STATE COLLEGE, PA.  FROM TESTIMONY FROM THE DRIVER THE ACCIDENT WAS DUE TO A PHYSICAL CONDITION THAT WAS UNFORESEEABLE.  THE DRIVER CLAIMS THAT HE HAD A MOMENTARY BLACKOUT.  THER IS NO MEDICAL RECORDS AVAILABLE TO DISPROVE OR SUPPORT THIS OCCURING.  THE TRUCK WAS CARRYING 6700 GALLONS OF #4 FUEL OIL.  THE SPILL WAS CAUSED WHEN THE TRAILER WAS OVERTURNED AND STRUCK THE GUARD RAIL.  THE GUARD RAIL CAUSED A PUNCTURE TO THE NOSE PLATE OF THE TRAILER RELEASING ALL 6700 GALLONS.  DUE TO THE QUICK RESPONSE OF THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARMENTS IN THE AREA THE OIL WAS CONTAINED AND WATER CONTAMINATION WAS PREVENTED.  CLEAN UP WAS DONE BY EAGLE TIRE AND TOWING OF MILESBURG, PA.  APPROXIMATELY 2000 TONS OF SOIL HAD TO BE REMOVED TO GET TO ALL OF THE AREAS THE OIL WORKED ITS WAY INTO . THE SOIL IS BEING TREATED AND RECYCLED BY GROSSER AND STEIGMAN OF HARRISBURG, PA.  THE AREA WAS REFILLED AND SEEDED.  ACCIDENTS LIKE THIS ONE ARE VERY HARD TO PREVENT OR PREDICT.  WE STRESS FOLLOWING DOT REGULATIONS IN REGARDS TO SCHEDULING DRIVER WORK DUTIES TO GIVE AMPLE TIME FOR REST TO PREVENT SUCH INCIDENTS.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLAODING A COMPARTMENT OF PLUS GASOLINE.  WHILE UNLOADING HE DISCOVERED THAT THE TANK WAS PAST THE OVERFILL READING.  HE WENT INTO THE STORE TO CALL THE DISPATCHER ON DUTY.  THE MANAGER OF THE STORE WENT BACK OUT TO THE DROPS AND THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE LITTING LOOKED EMPTY SO HE PROCEEDED TO PULL OFF THE FITTING.  GAS STARTED COMING OUT AND FLOWING DOWN THE DRAGE OF THE PARKING LOT  THE MANAGER OF THE STORE RAN THE FAUCET ONTO THE PARKING LOT.

THE SPLIT WAS REPAIRED WITH REPAIR PUDDY AND THEN TRANSFERRED TO A RECOVERY DRUM TO BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DRUM WAS IN VERY POOR SHAPE AND PRETTY BANGED UP IN THAT IT LOOKED AS IF IT HAD BEEN USED VERY OFTEN.  *THE SIDES OF THE DRUM WERE DENTED IN VARIOUS PLACES AND THE BOTTOM AND TOP WERE ALSO DENTED AND IT WAS ALSO NOTICED THAT THIS DRUM HAD BEEN REPAINTED AND SOME OF THAT PAINT WAS CHIPPING AWAY.

WHEN OUR DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO PUMP THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE THE GASKETS ON HIS PUMP STARTED LEAKING.  HE SHUT DOWN, CHANGED THE GASKETS AND PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD WITHOUT FURTHER DIFFICULTY.  THE SPILL AREA WAS TAKEN CARE OF BY THE CUSTOMER.

WHILE AT THE TRUCK STOP OUR DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL DRIP FROM THE BELLY OF THE TANK.  ABSORBENT WAS USED TO ABSORB THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND THE REST WAS CAUGHT IN A PAIL UNTIL THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER. COMPANY PERSONNEL WHO HAD RESPONDED CLEANED UP THE SPILLED AREA.

AFTER HEATING THE PRODUCT & MAKING A NITROGEN APPLICATION FOR PRESSURE UNLOADING, THE TANK STARTED LEAKING NEAR THE BOTTOM CENTER OF THE VESSEL. PRESSURE WAS RELEASED, ABSORBENT APPLIED AND A PUMP WAS USED TO COMPLETE THE UNLOADING.

STEEL PIPING WAS LOADED ON TOP OF DRUMS. 3 DRUMS COLLAPSED FROM THE EXCESIVE WEIGHT AND RUPTURED SPILLING APPROX. 1/3 OF THE MATERIAL FROM EACH DRUM (APPROX. TOTAL OF 55 GAL) LOADING PROCEDURES AREA BEING REVIEWED TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. WAS DISPATCHED TO GE FANUC AUTOMATION N.A., INC. LOCATED AT ROUTE 29N IN CHARLOTTESVILLE, VA TO PICK UP A LOAD OF LEAD CONTAMINATED WASTEWATER FOR DISPOSAL. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SITE.THE VEHICLE OPERATOR BEGAN TO LOAD THE PRODUCT INTO THE TANK. ONCE FULL, THE VEHICLE OPERATOR PREPARED THE VEHICLE FOR TRANSPORTATION AND DURING HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION DISCOVERED THAT THE PRODUCT HAD ENTERED THE SCRUBBER UNIT OF THE VACCUM TANK. THE DRIVER MANUALLY DRAINED THE SCRUBBER UNITS ON THE VEHICLE AND INSPECTED THEM TO MAKE SURE THEY WERE EMPTY. ONCE THIS OPERATION WAS COMPLETED, THE VEHICLE OPERATOR  STARTED THE VEHICLE IN ORDER TO BEGIN TRANSPORTING THE LOAD TO THE DESTINATION LOCATION. UPON STARTING THE ENGINE, HOWEVER, APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL VENTED FROM THE VENT PIPE OF THE SCRUBBER UNIT ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD OF THE LOADING AREA. THE VEHICLE WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN AND THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED INTO STORAGE PENDING FUTURE DISPOSAL TO A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE MATERIAL THAT WAS VENTED FROM THE VECHICLE ORIGINATED IN THE HOSE CONNECTED TO THE SCRUBBER UNIT. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO PHYSICALLY CHECK NOT ONLY THE SCRUBBER UNIT BUT ALL HOSES CONNECTED TO IT PRIOR TO DEPARTING A LOADING OR UNLOADING SITE AND TO DRAIN ALL RESIDUAL MATERIAL INTO THE APPROPRIATE CONTAINER.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND ,INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF NATICK, INC. LOCATED IN NATICK, MA IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT OF THE FACILITY. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY PLACED CONTAINMENT PAILS UNDER THE LEAK, ABSORBED THE RELEASED MATERIAL WITH A SUITABLE ABSORBENT AND INITIATED NOTIFICAITON PROCEDURES. A CLEAN HARBORS CLEAN-UP CREW RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AND INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  UPON EXAMINATION OF THE CARGO, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE SIDE SEAM OF THE CONTAINER HAD CRACKED ALLOWING MATERIAL TO ESCAPE ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. THE MATERIAL GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE CLEAN-UP OPERATION WAS CONTAINERIZED AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL THROUGH CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE INC. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERES AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS(I.E. OVERPACKING A LEAKING OR QUESTIONABLE CONTAINER) IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED ENROUTE.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD, VA SERVICE CENTER, THE DRIVER OF THE CLEAN HARBORS RICHMOND, VA SERVICE CENTER, THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE WAS LOADING ADDITIONAL CONTAINERS ONTO THE VEHICLE. WHILE LOADING, THE DRIVER DROPPED ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE DRIVER AND PERSONNEL FROM THE RICHMOND SERVICE CENTER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY. ALL ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER USED TO TRANSPORT THE MATERIAL TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO UTILIZE DRUM CARTS EQUIPPED WITH A SUITABLE SECUREMENT DEVICE WHEN LOADING OR UNLOADING CONTAINER.

column168: WHILE REMOVING SKIDS, DOCKWORKER PUNCTURED ONE CARTON WITH THE FORKLIFT BLADES.  THE SPILL WAS ISOALED AND CHEMTREC CALLED.  AN MSDS WAS OBATINED FOR THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND THE AREA WAS CLEANED.

PAILS WERE APPARENTLY STACKED ON SKID WITH THE LIDS OVERLAPPING. VIBRATION IN TRANSIT CAUSED THE LIDS TO WORK LOOSE AND THREE PAILS LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED, THE PRODUCT IDENTIFIED AND CHEMTREC CONTACTED.  ALL SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED AS INSTRUCTED.

DOCKWORKER STRUCK ONE CARTON WITH THE FORKLIFT BLADE, DAMAGING THE INNER CONTAINER AND ALLOWING MATERIAL TO RELEASE.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND THE MATERIAL IDENTIFIED.  THE SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENT AND THE AREA CLEANED.

DRIVER NOTED LEAKAGE WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY AND NOTIFIED DISPATCHER.  THE INNER CONTAINERS APPARENTLY CRACKED DUE TO ROAD VIBRATION AND RELEASED THE MATERIAL INTO THE CARTON.  CLEAN HARBORS WAS CONTRACTED TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN THE SPILLAGE.

TANK WAS INSIDE BUILDING OUT OF VIEW OF DRIVER. TANK WOULD NOT HOLD ALL PRODUCT ORDERED, AND SOME OVERFLOWED.  PLANT OPERATOR CLEANED UP SPILL.

OUR DIRVER WAS HOOKED UP WITH THE PROPER UNLOADING HOSE TO A FOUR BOLT FLANGE ON THE CONSIGNEE'S UNLOADING LINE.  WHEN HE OPENED THE SAFETY VALVE ON THE CARGO TANK STARTING THE ACID TO FLOW THE FLANGE ON THE CONSIGNEE'S LINE STARTED TO LEAK.  A SMALL STREAM OF ACID SPRAYED ON THE DRIVER'S ACID SUIT AND UNDER HIS FACE SHIELD OVER HIS GOGGLES AND A SMALL AMOUNT GOT ON HIS FOREHEAD.  HE WASHED IF OFF AT THE SAFETY SHOWER IMMEDIATELY.  THE CONSIGNEE INSISTED THEY TAKE HIM TO ST ANTHONY'S HOSPITAL.  THEY CHECKED HIMN AND RELEASED HIM TO RETURN TO WORK.  HE ONLY HAD A SLIGHT REDNESS OF THE SKIN ABOUT THE SIZE OF A DIME ON HIS FOREHEAD.

ACFX 77793 WAS NOTICED TO BE EMITTING VAPORS WHEN IT WAS MOVED WITH A YARD ENGINE.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  THE MIST LANDED ON THE SKIN OF 6 EMPLOYEES BUT THERE WERE NO SIGNIFICANT INJURIES TO HOSPITALIZE.  SHIPPER SENT REPRESENTATIVE WHO REPAIRED THE TORN MANWAY GASKET, ON SEPT 3,1993.

ECUX 374048 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING BY A CARRIER EMPLOYEE.  CAR WAS ISOLATED.  LEAK WAS STOPPED AT 3:30 PM WHEN A LOOSE GASKET ON THE LIQUID LINE WAS TIGHTENED.  EXXON WAS NOTIFIED TO SEND SOMEONE TO INSPECT AND MAKE OTHER REPAIRS IF NECESSARY.

GATX 80814 WAS NOTICED TO BE LEAKING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR OUT OF THE DOME AREA, BY A CARRIER EMPLOYEE.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SOURCE OF LEAK WAS A RUPTURED SAFETY VENT DISC.  SHIPPER SENT OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR, WHO REPLACED THE FAULTY DISC.

column168: DRIVER OVERFILLED CUSTOMERS TANK CAUSING SPILL.
AFTER COMPLETING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, DRIVER DRAINED HOSES CAUSING SPILL.

OUR DIRVER ARRIVED AT HIS DESTINATION, CHECKED IN WITH THE GUARD AND WAS DIRECTED TO THE UNLOADING AREA.  HE WAS MET BY THE RECEIVER WHO CHECKED THE SHIPPING DOCUMENTS AND INFORMED THE DRIVER THAT THE PLANT PERSONNEL WOULD HANDLE THE UNLOADING.  THE DRIVER TOLD THEM HE WOULD BE IN HIS TRACTOR DOING PAPER WORK.  THE PLANT PERSONNEL PROCEEDED TO START THE DELIVERY AND A SHORT TIME LATER OUR DRIVER HEARD A WHISTLING NOISE AND EXITED HIS TRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE.  THE NOISE GOT LOUDER AND WAS JOINED BY A RUMBLING SOUND AND AT THIS POINT THE TOP OF THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK BLEW OFF, SPEWING A CLOUD OF VAPOR.  OUR DRIVER EXITED THE AREA ALONG WITH THE PLANT PERSONNEL.  IT WAS LATER DETERMINED THAT THE PLANT PERSONNEL UNLOADED THE MATERIAL INTO THE WRONG STORAGE TANK.  THE CUSTOMER ACCEPTED FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE INCIDENT AND HANDLED ALL CLEAN UP.  THE FIGURES ON EVACUATIONS AND INJURIES WERE OBTAINED FROM NEWSPAPER CLIPPINGS.  ITEMS MARKED IN SECTIONS 41 THRU 45 REFER TO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK AND NOT THE CARGO TANK.  THE CARGO TANK DID NOT FAIL.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: ON 9/16/93 WE RECIEVED ATLANTA TR#4956 INTO ORLANDO. WHEN WE UNLOADED THIS SHIPMENT, THE DOCKMAN NOTED THAT ONE OF THE DRUMS WAS LEAKING. AS FAR AS WE CAN TELL, THE DRUM HAD BEEN HIT BY A FORK LIFT BLADE AND MOST LIKEY WAS DONE WHEN LOADED IN ATLANTA. WE PLACED THE DRUM INTO OUR HAZARDOUS BAY LAYING ON IT'S SIDE ON A PLT SO WE COULD STOP THE LEAK. WE CONTACTED THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION AND THEY ADVISED THAT WE COULD RETURN TO THEM IN A RECOVERY DRUM. WE DID THIS. AS FOR THE ESTIMATED 10 GALLONS OF RESIN THAT LEAKED OUT, WE CLEANED UP WITH DRY ABSORBANT GRANUELS AND DISPOSED OF. THIS ALSO HAS BEEN REPORTED TO THE SAFETY DIRECTOR FOR AAA COOPER TRANSPORTATION, DAVE COLLINS THE ATLANTA TERMINAL HAS TO ALSO BE ADVISED OF WHAT HAPPENED CAUSING THIS LEAKAGE.
UNIT WAS PARKED ON YARD. SOMEONE OPENED INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES CAUSING SPILL.

THE CONTAINER WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING, 8 PEOPLE SMELLED THE PRODUCT, AND WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND CHECKED AS A PRECAUTION. THEY WERE RELEASED THAT NIGHT. THE CONTAINER WAS REMOVED FROM THE FLATCAR AND PLACED INTO ISOLATION AND TRANLOADED. 2 DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE DAMAGED TO A LEAKING CONDITION AS THE RESULT OF INSUFFICIENT BLOCKING AND BRACING. AFTER TRANSLOADING INTO CONTAINER NUMBER NYKU232500 THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED.

column168: DRIVER WAS LOADED WITH #2 BOF SHOP DUST AT LTV IN CLEVELAND, OHIO. MATERIAL IS LOADED THROUGH A SPECIAL FLAP OPENING ON THE TARP TO MINIMIZE THE AMOUNT OF DUST THAT ESCAPES.  DRIVER STATED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS LOADED AGAINST THE TAILGATE WITHOUT HIS KNOWLEDGE. AFTER DRIVER FINISHED LOADING HE PROCEEDED TOWARDS THE SCALES.  AS HE CROSSED THE RAILROAD TRACKS IN THE PLANT, THE TAILGATE POPPED OPEN AND THE DUST FELL TO THE GROUND. PERSONNEL FOR LTV'S ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL RESPONDED WITHIN MINUTES WITH A VAC-ALL TO COLLECT THE MATERIAL THAT SPILLED.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS THEN DUMPED INTO LTV'S SLUDGE PIT ALONG WITH THE REMAINING MATERIAL IN THE DUMP TRAILER.  ONCE THE DRIVER UNLOADED HIS TRAILER COMPLETELY, HE WAS DISPATCHED TO OUR TERMINAL SO THAT WE COULD INSPECT THE TRAILER,  UPON INSPECTION, WE FOUND NO DEFECTS IN THE EQUIPMENT.  WHAT WE HAVE DOME TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS WERE TO ADD MORE EXTERNAL LOCKS ONTO THE TAILGATE AS AN EXTRA PRECAUTION.  WE  HAVE ALSO INSTRUCTED DRIVERS TO MAKE SURE THE MATERIAL (WHEN LOADED) IS NOT RESTING AGAINST THE TAILGATE.  THIS WILL PREVENT ANY UNNEEDED PRESSURE AGAINST THE GATE. NOTE: SECTION III NO. 11 - NO MANIFEST WAS PROVIDED BECAUSE THE LOAD WAS EMPTIED FROM THE TRAILER SO THAT WE COULD INSPECT THE TRAILER AT OUR FACILITY.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT CHEMTECH IN WAMPUM, PA AT 3:00 PM.  AS DRIVER WAS WAITING IN LINE, HE NOTICED FLUID DRIPPING FROM HIS OVERLOW TUBE. THERE WAS LESS THAT A GALLON THAT SPILLED AND CHEMTECH HANDLED THE DISPOSAL OF THE OIL DRY.  ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS WERE TO CHANGE THE KNIFE VALVE AND INSTRUCT DRIVERS TO CHECK ALL VALVES ON TANKS DURING THEIR ROUTINE INSPECTIONS WHEN IN ROUTE.

column168: I WAS NOTIFIED ON SEPTEMBER 26, 1993 THAT A PIPE ON OUR TRAILER HAD A PIN HOLE IN IT AND THAT APPROXIMATELY 4 OZ OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED ONTO THE CEMENT IN CONTAINMENT.  CHEMTECH PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE SPILL WITH OIL DRY AND DISPOSED OF THE MATERIALS.  WE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED OUR MAINTENANCE PEOPLE WHO WERE ABLE TO PATCH THE HOLE AND RETURN THE TANK TO OUR TERMINAL.  WE THEN REPLACED THE ENTIRE OVERFLOW UNIT TO CORRECT THE PROBLEM.  TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS TYPE, WE HAVE INSTRUCTED ALL DRIVERS AND MAINTENANCE PEOPLE TO BE ESPECIALLY CAUTIOUS IN THEIR INSPECTIONS OF THESE AREAS.  THEREFORE, EQUIPMENT WITH THE LEAST AMOUNT OF DAMAGE CAN BE TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE AND EITHER REPAIRED OR REPLACED BEFORE IT IS PLACED BACK IN SERVICE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON SEPTEMBER 8, 1993 JUST BEFORE 7:00 PM, DRIVER DANIEL WICKSTROM WAS TAKING THE RAMP OFF OF MEMORIAL HIGHWAY (#60) ONTO EASTBOUND INTERSTATE #75 (A TWO LANE BLACKTOP RAMP).  HIS REPORTED SPEED AT THAT TIME WAS 30 MPH.  HE WAS TRAVELING IN THE RIGHT LANE.  ABOUT 25 FEET ONTO THE RAMP HE FELT THE WEIGHT OF THE TRUCK SHIFT LEFT TOWARDS THE OUTSIDE OF THE CURVE. HE LOOKED TO THE LEFT AND SAW A CAR THERE IN THAT LANE, TRAVELING AT A HIGHER RATE OF SPEED.  HE ATTEMPTED TO STRAIGHTEN OUT WITHIN HIS LANE, SLOWING TO A REPORTED SPEED OF 25 MPH.  HE THEN SAW THE RIGHT REAR TANDEMS LEAVE THE GROUND.  AFTER THE CAR PASSED, HE ATTEMPTED TO REGAIN THE BALANCE OF HIS VEHICLE BY STRAIGHTENING OUT SOME MORE, BUT THE TRAILER WAS ALREADY ON ITS WAY OVER.  THE FORCE OF THE TRAILER ROLLING OVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED THE TRACTOR OVER ON ITS SIDE.  BOTH THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER SLID ABOUT 20 FEET (ON THEIR RIGHT SIDES) ACROSS THE LEFT LANE AND ONTO THE GRASSY SHOULDER.  DISCHARGE AND VENT VALVES WERE BROKEN OFF, CAUSING THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER TO BEGIN SPILLING OUT.  THE INJURED DRIVER CRAWLED OUT OF THE TRACTOR AND CALLED FOR EMERGENCY HELP USING THE CELLULAR PHONE OF AN ASSISTING MOTORIST STOPPED BEHIND HIM.  HE CALLED TO NOTIFY OUR NIGHT MANAGER, RICK MURPHY AT APPROXIMATELY 7:00 PM. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED QUICKLY AT THE SCENE AND WITHIN APPROXIMATELY 15 MINUTES HAD SECURED THE LEAK.  APPROXIMATELY THREE TO FOUR HUNDRED GALLONS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE (BLEACH) SPILLED ONTO THE GRASSY AREA BETWEEN 7:00 PM AND 7:15 PM TO 7:30 PM.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED THE EPA AND DER RIGHT AWAY.  THE NIGHT MANAGER IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED AN EMPTY TANKER AND TWO AVAILABLE EMPLOYEES TO THE SCENE AND CONTACTED UNIVERSAL WASTE AND TRANSIT TO HANDLE THE CLEAN-UP.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE SPILL WAS CONFIRMED AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE STATE WARNING POINT WERE NOTIFIED THERE FROM THE SCENE AT 8:37 PM.  THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE OVERTURNED TRAILER WERE PUMPED INTO THE DISPATCHED TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS HAULED BACK TO OUR PLANT LOCATION FOR STORAGE AND DAMAGE EVALUATION.  THE TRACTOR WAS RETURNED TO PENSKE TRUCK LEAKING IN TAMPA.  UNIVERSAL WASTE AND TRANSIT COMPLETED THE CLEAN-UP OF THE SPILL.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO A NEARBY HOSPITAL FOR EMERGENCY CARE.  THE AREA OF THE ACCIDENT IS CLASSIFIED AS A BUSINESS/SHOPPING AREA.  THERE WAS NO REPORTED EXPOSURE TO INDIVIDUALS OR OTHER VEHICULAR OR PROPERTY DAMAGE AT THE SCENE.  AS THE CHEMICAL WAS IN LIQUID FORM, IT DID NOT POSE ANY THREAT OF POTENTIAL HEALTH RISK TO PERSONS OFFSITE EITHER.  IN SUMMARY, THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, COUNTY EMERGENCY MEDICAL AND LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT REPRESENTATIVES PROVIDED EMERGENCY ASSISTANCE ON THE SCENE. IN ADDITION TO THESE AGENCIES, THE EPA, STATE DER, STATE DNR AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT #196739) WERE ALL NOTIFIED CONCERNING THIS ACCIDENT.

THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINSTRATION WAS CONTACTED AT 201/645-3701 WHERE SPECIAL AGENT GREG JONES WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  THE PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. column168: ON 09-15-93, SORT SUPERVISOR, MIKE BALLEIN, REPORTED A SPILL TO ILN HAZ MAT DISPATCH VIA RADIO AT 0111.  THIS SPILL WAS ON THE PROPERTY OF AIRBORNE EXPRESS, INC., 145 HUNTER DR., WILMINGTON, OH 45177, AND LOCATED IN THE "A" BUILDING AT DOOR "A-11".  RANDY WILLIAMS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST AND MATT RAGER, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, WERE ON THE SCENE AT 0114.  MATT PERFORMED A OH TEST.  THE TEST PAPER TURNED RED, INDICATING A STRONG ACID.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION AN ELECTRIC STORAGE BATTERY WAS FOUND ON ITS SIDE INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX.  MISC. CAMERA EQUIPMENT WAS ALSO FOUND INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX.  THIS BATTERY HAD NO PROTECTION OVER THE TERMINALS TO PREVENT A SHORT CIRCUIT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS BAGGED, TAGGED, AND REMVOED FROM THE AREA.  ALL RESIDUE WAS CLEANED UP AND THIS SHIPMENT WAS TAKEN TO THE HAZ MAT SORT AREA, PLACED INTO THE SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY, PENDING AN FAA INVESTIGATION.

AT 1040 HRS ON 092493 MGR. CHEMICAL TRANSPORATION SAFETY HARRY W. RODBOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY BY MR. CECIL HARRIS THE CAR FORMAN AT ELKO NEVADA, REGARDING TANKCAR KCCX2510, IT IS REPORTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. STAN ANDERSON) TO CHECK ON THIS CAR TO SEE IF THERE ARE ANY MECHANICAL DEFICIENCIES THAT MIGHT CONTRIBUTE TO THE CONTINUTING PROBLEMS WITH THIS CAR.

ABOUT 8 MILES FROM BLOOMINGTON. SMITH CONTACTED VERON SHIRLEY, LEADER OF THE BP CHEMICAL HAZMAT TEAM. THE BP HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND HAD THE RUPTURE DISK REPLACED IN LESS THAN 45 MINS.

SWITCH CREW WAS PREPARING TO SPOT THIS CAR AT THE CONSIGNEE WHEN THEY NOTICED IT SLOSHING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP. THEY NOTIFIED MTO SKINNER AND PLANT SUPERINTENDENT CHARLES HUGGINS. A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE CAR SPOTTED WITHOUT DELAY. CHEMTREC NOTIFIED.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: CONTAINER SET ON GROUND, IN ERROR, AT KANSAS CITY 09/16/93. ON 09/21, A RAMP EMPLOYEE NOTED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE END OF THE CONTAINER. THE KANSAS CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND LOCAL REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER RESPONDED AT THAT TIME; THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DETERMINED THAT NO EMERGENCY EXISTED, AND THE SHIPPER'S LOCAL REPRESENTATIVE CLEANED UP SPILLAGE. THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED WITH A BULK SOLID; THE LIQUID THAT HAD LEAKED OUT IS BELIEVED TO BE RAINWATER THAT HAD SEEPED INTO THE LOAD THROUGH THE TOP COVERS. TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE, ONE END OF THE CONTAINER WAS LIFTED APPROXIMATELY 2 FT. AND PLACED ON BLOCKS, TO FORCE LIQUID TO THE OPPOSITE END OF THE CONTAINER. ABSORBENT WAS PUT BENEATH THE POINT OF THE LEAK AS A PRECAUTION, AND THE INTERIOR THEN REPAIRED BY KURT ECKEL OF USPCI.

column168: S/AM BALLANCE RECEIVED A REPORT FROM DAVID STRAIN OF UPMF THAT CONTAINER APLU-458055 WAS FOUND LEAKING WHEN IT ARRIVED OAKLAND. S/A, BALLANCE WAS MEET ON SCENE BY THE OAKLAND FIRE DEPT. THE CONTAINER WAS REMOVED FORM THE FLATCAR AND PLACED ONTO PLASTIC. THE SEWER DRAIN NEAR THE CONTAINER WAS ALSO SEALED WITH PLASTIC. THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED AND FOUND TO HAVE ONLY ONE STRIP OF REINFORCED PACKING TAPE. TWO BAGS OF OF DICHLOROBENZENE MIXTURE WERE FOUND WITH SLIGHT TEARS IN THE SIDE. THESE BAGS WERE PLACED INTO LARGER PLASTIC BAGS. AFTER REMOVING SEVERAL PALLETS OF PRODUCTS, A 275 GALLON CONTAINER OF SULFURIC ACID WAS FOUND. THE SIX INCH BLACK CAP HAD BEEN SET IN PLACE AND WAS WRENCH TIGHT. THE TWO INCH CENTER CAP WAS FOUND ON THE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER. THE PRODUCT WAS SPLASHING OUT THROUGH THE TWO INCH HOLE. THE CAP WAS REPLACED AND TIGHTENED WITH A WRENCH. THREE CASES OF GARBAGE TIGHTENED WITH A WRENCH. THREE CASES OF GARBAGE BAGS WERE SATURATED WITH THE SULFURIC ACID. THESE CASES WERE DISPOSED OF WITH OTHER WASTE MATERIAL. STATE OES WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND PUC WAS ALSO ON SCENE.

column168: RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM THE MYIO AT OGDEN, THAT TANK CAR GATX49252 WAS LEAKING AND HAD BEEN SET OUT FOR REPAIR. THE CAR WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE SAFETY VALVE ASSEMBLY. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND INDICATED THAT THEY WOULD SEND TWO TECHNICIANS TO ASSIST WITH A TRANSLOAD. ALSO INDICATED THAT THEY WANTED IT LOADED INTO TANK TRUCKS AND ARRANGED TO HAVE MATLACK TRUCK DISPATCH TRUCKS TO THE SIGHT. TRANSFER OPERATIONS SCHEDULED TO COMMENCE ON SUNDAY THE 19TH AS MATLACK WAS TIED UP UNTIL THAT TIME. REG MGR. DEAN WHITELEY, MGR. DON LOW, MGR. SANDY COVI AND SPECIALIST RODABOUGH IN CONJUNCTION WITH MR. KNIGHT AND MR RUDOLPH OF J.R. SIMPLOT WERE ON HAND WHEN THE TRANSLOAD COMMENCED AT 1440 HRS. VAPOR PRESSURE WAS USED TO MOVE THE PRODUCT. MATLACK PROVIDED A CORKIN COMPRESSOR. THE TANK CAR WAS PIPED THROUGH THE VAPOR LINE, PULLING THE PRESSURE OFF THE TRUCK INTO THE TANK CAR UNTIL THE PRESSURE OF THE TANKCAR WAS 110 PSI. TRANSLOAD OPERATIONS COMPLETE AT 1950 HRS. FINISHED THE OPERATION BY WASHING THE REMAINING VAPOR IN THE TANKCAR WAS 110 PSI. TRANSLOAD OPERATIONS COMPLETE AT 1950 HRS. FINISHED THE OPERATION BY WASHING THE REMAINING VAPOR IN THE TANK CAR TO BRING THE CAR DOWN TO 0 PSI. WASHED THE VAPORS IN 8000 GALLON OF WATER, WHICH WAS RETURNED TO J.R. SIMPLOT. ALL OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETE AT 1230 HRS ON 092193. SHIPPER NOTIFIED AS WELL AS CHEMTREC. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO J.R.SIMPLOT, WHERE IT WILL BE SHOPPED FOR REPAIR.

RECEIVED INFORMATION FROM MYIO AT SALT LAKE REPORTING THAT TANK CAR KCCX2510 HAD BEEN SET OUT FOR REPAIR, IT IS REPORTEDLY LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. THE CAR WAS SET OUT IN THE RUNNING RAIL POCKET, PENDING AN INSPECTION. UPON ARRIVAL AT 1200 091893, THE CAR WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO HAVE A BROKEN FRANGIBLE DISC. THIS WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR WAS WASHED DOWN WITH A SOLUTION OF WATER AND SODE BICARBONATE REPAIR OF CAR COMPLETE AT 1305HRS. NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WITH THIS CAR, CHEMTREC NOTIFED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

WHILE MAKING TANKCAR INSPECTIONS IN THE ELKO NEVADA YARD TANK CAR HCPX2306 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE STUFFING BOX ON THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. CHECK OF THE BOX REVEALED THAT THERE WAS NO PACKING, ALLOWING THE CONTENTS TO SPLASH OUT AND RUN DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR. REPAIR CONSISTED OF REPACKING THE BOX WITH TEFLON PACKING MATE RIAL AND TIGHTENING THE PACKING GLAND NUT, THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED WITHOUT FURTHER PROBLEMS.

ON 091893 AT APPROXIMATELY 500AM MTO STONE DISCOVERED A VAPOR CLOUD EXTENDING ABOUT 1 FOOT FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING OF THIS CAR. HE HAD THE TRAIN SET THE CAR OUT. REEDER RECEIVED THE CALL AND TRAVELED TO AMELIA YARD. USING PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, REEDER OPENED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND FOUND THE A END LIQUID VALVE LEAKING LIQUID AMMONIA. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED. THE PRESSURE INSIDE THE CAR WAS 170PSI. REEDER WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE PLUG IN THE VALVE AND STOP THE LEAK. FARMLAND INDUSTRIES WAS NOTIFIED AND THE CAR RETURNED TO THEIR PLANT FOR REPAIR.

column168: WHILE MAKING TANKCAR INSPECTIONS IN THE ELKO NEVADA YARD, TANK CAR HCPX2314 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING, FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE. LEAK WAS STOPPED BY TIGHTENING THE BOLTS AROUND THE FLANGE. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AS INDICATED IN THE REPORT. THERE WERE NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WITH THIS CAR.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: SP AGT. SMITH WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS SPILLING LIQUID FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR DURING SWITCHING MOVEMENTS.  INSPECTION REVEALED THE MANWAY GASKET TO BE OLD, BRITTLE, AND OUT OF PLACE.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPPER CALLED TO APPROVE THE PLACEMENT OF NEW GASKET MATERIAL.  THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED AT 1510 HRS.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE ON TO DESTINATION.  SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THAT FOUR LOCKING LUGS AND THE MANWAY WERE LESS THAN HAND TIGHT.  SMITH WAS ASSURED THAT THE LOADING PROCEDURE WOULD BE CHECKED.

AT 1120HRS ON 9-17-93 WHILE CONDUCTING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION ON TANK CAR GATX 21206 CONTAINING (RESIDUE) DENATURED ALCOHOL, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN1986; MGR CTS FRANK LERCH NOTED RESIDUE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT THE RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 40 DROPS A MINUTE.  MGR. LERCH IMMEDIATELY TIGHTENED TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE 3/4 TURN WHICH SECURED CAR.  CONTINUED INSPECTION OF CAR DEVELOPED THE ADDITIONAL EXCEPTIONS NOTED.  1. BOTTOM OUTLET CAP LOOSE; TIGHTENED 2 TURNS.  2. 6 SWINGBOLTS TO MANWAY COVER HAND TIGHT; TIGHTENED SAME.  3. LIQUID VALVE PLUG LOOSE; TIGHTENED 3 TURNED.  4. 4" INSPECTION/QUICK FILL HOLE CAP NOT SECURED TO MANWAY COVER BY SAFETY CHAIN.  5. LEFT PLACARD MISSING; REPLACED.  AT 1550 ON 9-17-93 MGR LERCH CONTACTED JIM GLANCEY, GENERAL MANAGER, BRIMM INDUSTRIES ADVISING OF NOTED EXCEPTIONS CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN AND NEEDED REPAIRS.  NOTIFICATIONS: 1430HRS, 9-17-93, CHEM-TREC, JIM LONG, #24589; 1440HRS, UPRR M.D.I. DOUG LANT; 1450HRS, NEBRASKA DEPARTMENT ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, NEIL HEIL, #091793-NH-1450; 1550HRS, JIM GLANCEY, GENERAL MANAGER, BRIMM ENERGY.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: WHILE MAKING TANKCAR INSPECTIONS IN THE NORTH YARD AT SALT LAKE CITY, UTAH.  SPECIALIST CTS, HARRY RODABOUGH DISCOVERED TANK CAR WRNX 30095 TO HAVE A LOOSE PALKING NUT ON THE GAUGING ROD.  THIS WAS QUICKLY AND EASILY REPAIRED BY TIGHTENING THE NUT.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEMS.

INSPECTED LOADED CAR CONTAINING MOLTEN SULFUR, ORM-C, UN2448 LOCATED ON EAST DEPARTURE TRACK 6; NOTING FRESH DRIED PRODUCT AROUND SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY.  UPON REMOVAL OF WEATHER CAP (STANDARD UTLX TYPE) OBSERVED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISK HAD FAILED.  REMOVED FAILED "OSECO" #100 DISK AND REPLACED WITH CDC #100 DISK WHICH SECURED CAR.  NOTIFICATIONS: 1150HRS, 9-16-93, CHEM-TREC, JIM MANNING, #24566; 1210HRS NEBRASKA DEPARTMENT ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, JIM BOROVICH, #091693-JB-1210; 1220HRS EXXON CO USA, TIM MULLEN, PLANT SUPERINTENDENT; 1445HRS, UPRR M.D.I., JOHN SMITH.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED VIA TELEPHONE BY MR. DENNIS KLEIV, MANAGER, TRANSPORTATION, ELF ATOCHEM, PORTLAND, OREGON, REPORTING TANK CAR ACFX 86536 HAD BEEN DELIVERED TO THEIR CUSTOMERS LEAD TRACK AND WAS SHOWING SIGNS OF LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE SAFETY VENT.  THE CUSTOMER HAD INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE RUPTURE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT HAD BURST.  IN ORDER TO OFF LOAD THE CARS CONTENTS, THE CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE PRESSURIZED, AND THE DISC WOULD HAVE TO BE REPLACED TO ACCOMPLISH THIS.  THE CONSIGNEE DID NOT HAVE A REPLACEMENT DISC AVAILABLE TO COMPLETE THIS TASK.  MANAGER COOPER MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO FLY TO MILPITAS AND REPLACE TH DISC.  THE SAFETY VENT , A STANDARD MIDLAND BAFFLE, WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE RUPTURE DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND STAINLESS/TEFLON BS&B DISC.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT FROM THE LEAD TRACK TO THE CUSTOMERS OFF LOADING FACILITY. NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE NOT MADE TO THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES, OR TO THE COUNTY OF SANTA CLARA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SERVICES.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings; Vent
column168: DURING INSPECTION OF TRAIN CYDE 13, EXTRA 6005 SOUTH, NOTED TANK CAR TGOX 21002, HAVING LIQUID COMING FROM TOP AREA.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT FRANGIBLE DISC, CDC-95-0, 100 # HAD RUPTURED.  REPLACED WITH BS&B 100# DISC, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  APPLIED SEAL: UP-C-54663.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT SAFETY VENT IS A MIDLAND 2 INCH AND WAS LOCATED OFF THE PLATFORM. JOE DEBMAN, CHEMTREC, FILE #24497 AND DEE BIRD, TRAFFIC MANAGER, NU WEST INDUSTRIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY BOB SCHUT, SUPERVISOR YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, THAT TANK CAR GATX 61133 WAS REPORTED TO HAVE A VERY STRONG ODOR EMITTING FROM THE CAR. THE EAST END SWITCHER WAS TO PULL THE CAR FROM THE RIP TRACK AND WAS IN THE PROCESS OF COUPLING INTO THE CAR WHEN THE SWITCHMAN NOTED THE ODOR. THERE WERE NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE, HOWEVER, THE ODOR PERSISTED. AS THE ENGINE WAS LOCATED DOWNWIND FROM THE CAR, THE CREW DECIDED TO LEAVE THE CAR IN PLACE AND EXIT THE RIP TRACK.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST RUPTURE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT.  THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND BAFFLE, WAS DISASSEMBLED, AND THE RUPTURE DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND PLASTIC OSECO DISC. THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND SECURE.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONSD WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE NOT MADE TO THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES, OR TO THE COUNTY OF SAN BERNARDINO DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SERVICES.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY (MCTS) S COVI WAS NOTIFIED BY J JONES, MECHANICAL FOREMAN, THAT TANK CAR KCCX 2224 WAS FOUND TO HAVE A FAILED FRANGIBLE DISC DURING FRA INSPECTION BY BRUCE MARRIOTT.  THE FAILED BS&B, 100 PSI, (MODEL TC) DISC WAS REPLACED WITH NEW BS&B, 100 PSI DISC WHICH SECURED THE CAR.  STAN ANDERSON OF KENNECOTT UTAH COPPER WAS NOTIFIED THE INCIDENT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: S/A, BALLANCE RECEIVED A REPORT FROM BOB STINERT OF UPMF THAT CONTAINER APLU-488030 JUST ARRIVED AND WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  S/A, BALLANCE AND THE STOCKTON FIRE DEPT WERE UNABLE TO MAKE ENTRY INTO THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER HAD BOXES HAND STACKED TO THE TOP.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO A LOADING RAMP.  MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED.  MORGAN ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND BEGAN REMOVING PRODUCT FROM THE CONTAINER.  EIGHT FIVE GALLON DRUMS WERE FOUND LEAKING. THEY HAD BEEN DAMAGED BY A SECOND PALLET CONTAINING METAL SHELVES.  THIS PALLET HAD BEEN PLACED ON TOP OF THE PALLET CONTAINING THE DRUMS.  THE DRUMS WERE DAMAGED ON THE LIDS AND SEVERAL HAD THE SIDES CRUSHED.  ONE ONE GALLON CAN OF PAINT WAS DAMAGED ON THE SIDE.  THE CAN HAD BEEN DAMAGED BY A PALLET THAT FELL.  THE CONTAINER WAS POORLY LOADED AND IMPROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED.

S/A, BALLANCE CONDUCTING INSPECTIONS OF TANKCARS ON THE SANTE FE TRANSFER TRACK FOUND TANKCAR ASTX-2056 WITH A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK.  THE TANKCAR WAS BEING TRANSFERED FROM THE SANTE FE TO THE UNION PACIFIC.  THE SANTE FE WAS ADVISED OF THE EXCEPTION AND THAT THE CAR WOULD NOT BE ACCEPTED UNTIL REPAIRS HAD BEEN MADE.  THE STOCKTON FIRE DEPT. WAS ALSO ADVISED.  THE SANTE FE ADVISED THEY WOULD NOT BE ABLE TO RESPOND FOR SEVERAL HOURS.  AT THEIR REQUEST S/A, BALLANCE COMPLETED THE REPLACEMENT OF THE RUPTURE DISK.

THE HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED OF A POSSIBLE SPILL ON SEPT. 21, 1993 AT 605.  ONE BOX FELL APART AT THE TRUCK DOCK AND BROUGHT TO THE HAZMAT AREA 1 BATTERY WAS FOUND LEAKING BATTERY ACID.  BOX WAS NOT MARKED HAZARDOUS NOR WAS ANY PAPERWORK OFFERED.  SHIPMENT WAS CONTAINERIZED AND PLACED IN THE DISPOSAL AREA AWAITING DISPOSITION BY THE FAA AND ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT.  JEFFREY A ROUTSON

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON 09/20/93 AT 0845HRS SPL AGT R.L. CERDA WAS ADVISED BY REGIONAL DIRECTOR O.R. LANE OF A LEAKING TANKCAR IN BLOOMINGTON, TX.  CAR UTLX12611 SHOWED TO BE LOADED WITH SULFURIC ACID AND WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  SPL AGENT CERDA ARRIVED AT 1315HRS AND LOCATED THE CAR AT 1330HRS. AFTER SECURING THE CAR, AGT CERDA INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE MANWAY GASKET HAD BEEN MISAPPLIED.  THE GASKET WAS REMOVED AND REAPPLIED.  THE CAR'S OTHER FITTINGS AND VALVES WERE INSPECTED.  WITH ALL SECURE, THE CAR WAS RELEASED AT 1400HRS.

column62: Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: S/A BALLANCE AND CTS, COOPER WERE ADVISED OF CONTAINER APLU-450745 ARRIVING OAKLAND LEAKING.  OAKLAND FIRE AND MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ON SCENE.  THE CONTAINER WAS LOWERED ONTO PLASTIC THAT WAS PLACED ON THE GROUND. A NEAR BY DRAIN WAS ALSO COVERED.  THE DECISION WAS MADE TO MAKE ENTRY.  ONE FIVE GALLONDRUM WAS FOUND TO BE EMPTY.  THE DRUM HAD WHAT APPEARED TO BE A SMALL NAIL HOLE ON THE BASE.  NO PROTRUSIONS WERE FOUND ON THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED FROM THE BASE OF THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS ON TOP OF CONTAINER ICSU-160840 AND IN CAR DTTX-72038.  BOTH CONTAINERS HAD SPILLAGE ON THEM.  THEY WERE CLEANED PRIOR TO ALLOWING THEM TO DEPART.

REG MGR. POLICE, P.A. MILLER NOTIFIED SPECIAL AGENT BOUDREAUX THAT TANK CAR GATX 96756 IN THE TAFT YARD, TAFT, LA. WAS LEAKING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  BOUDREAUX & MILLER RESPONDED, AND WHILE ENROUTE MADE NOTIFICATION TO EMERGENCY RESPONDER ORGANIZATIONS OF ST. CHARLES PARISH. AGENTS BOUDREAUX & MILLER MET WITH ST. CHARLES FIRE DEPT. RESPONDER, REGINALD GAUBERT & ST. CHARLES PARISH SHERIFF'S DEPUTY RICH MEGUER.  UNION CARBIDE SUPERVISOR, JIM ELLIS ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND WAS SHOWN THE LEAKING TANK CAR.  LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAZ/MAT HOTLINE (CYNTHIA) WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  AGENT BOUDREAUX DONNED PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND UPON OPENING THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER, NOTED THAT THE GASEOUS LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE GAUGING DEVICE VALVE WHICH WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION.  IT WAS NOTED THAT THE GAUGING ROD WAS EXTREMELY CORRODED AND WOULD NOT MOVE DOWNWARD TO RELEASE THE ROD SAFETY DEVICE.  AGENT BOUDREAUX WAS ABLE TO TURN THE RODS VALVE ONE QUARTER OF A TURN COUNTER CLOCKWISE WHICH WAS ENOUGH TO TIGHTEN THE VALVE AND STOP THE LEAK.  ALL LIQUID AND VAPOR LINES AND PLUGS WERE CHECKED AND TIGHTENED.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT ALL 4 PLACARDS HAD NOT BEEN REVERSED.  PLACARDS WERE TURNED TO THE PROPER SIDES. LA. STATE POLICE HAZ/MAT HOTLINE (CYNTHIA) NOTIFIED THAT THE LEAK HAD BEEN STOPPED.  C F INDUSTRIES NOTIFIED AND THEY ADVISED THAT THEY WOULD NOTIFY CAIRO COOP EQUITY.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: S/A BALLANCE AND CTS, COOPER WERE NOTIFIED THAT TANKCAR NATX-37590 WAS LEAKING.  THEY ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND BEGAN INSPECTING THE TANKCAR.  THE BOLTS LOCATED ON THE MANWAY WERE FOUND TO BE LOOSE.  THE VACCUM RELEASE VALVE WAS ALSO FOUND TO BE STUCK OPEN.  THE VALVE WAS PARTIALLY DISASSEMBLED WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE.  THE VALVE WAS THEN PLACED BACK TOGETHER.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND ASKED TO INSPECT THE VACCUM RELEASE VALVE.

CAR WAS OBSERVED AT ADDIS, LOUISIANA WITH A SMALL VAPOR RELEASE COMING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AT ADDIS WITH OUT INCIDENT OR OFF SITE IMPACT.  MR BOB LENZER, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS AT ADDIS, CONTACTED REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, T.M. ROBINSON.  ROBINSON, WHO WAS IN SPRING, TEXAS, CONTACTED TRIAD CHEMICAL AT DONALDSONVILLE, LOUISIANA FOR ASSISTANCE.  UPON NOTIFICATION, MR STEVE LANDRY AND MR. BOB MCKEE OF TRIAD CHEMICAL RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE PACKING RETAINER ON THE "A" END LIQUID VALVE.  THE RETAINER WAS TIGHTENED AND THIS SECURED THAT CAR FROM LEAKING.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  ROBINSON CONTACTED MR LEROY HENSON, PRODUCTION SUPERVISOR FOR TEXACO CHEMICAL, AND RELATED THE DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: S/A BALLANCE RECEIVED A REPORT FROM THE STOCKTON TOWER THAT TANKCAR NATX-29948 WAS LEAKING.  S/A, BALLANCE ARRIVED AND FOUND LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE TOP OPERATING VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE A FULL 1/4 TURN OPEN.  THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED.  THE LIQUID POOLED IN THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS DRAINED INTO A BUCKET, THE LIQUID WAS THEN PLACED INTO A USPCI CONTAINER LOCATED AT THE DEISEL SHOP.

DURING NORMAL TRAIN OPERATIONS AT ADDIS, LOUISIANA A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPLASHED FROM BENEATH THE MANWAY COVER.  THE PRODUCT SPLASHED ONTO UPRR TRAINMEN E. J. MILLER.  MILLER IMMEDIATELY MADE USE OF AN EMERGENCY SHOWER THAT WAS LOCATED NEARBY.  THIS ACTION PREVENTED ANY INJURY TO MILLER.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED AT ADDIS WITH OUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  UPRR MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATION BOB LENZER CONTACTED THE DOW PLANT AT PLAQUEMINE AND REQUESTED HELP WITH SECURING THE CAR.  MR DEAN SMITH, EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR FOR DOW AND 3 TECHNICIANS RESPONDED. INSPECTION BY DOW PERSONNEL REVEALED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS BECAUSE ALL 6 OF THE MANWAY LID SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE.  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THIS SECURED THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT TO DOW'S PLANT.  REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED OF THIS INCIDENT ON MONDAY, 10/4/93, BY MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE GREG SHORT.  AFTER VERIFYING THAT MILLER HAD NOT SUSTAINED INJURY ROBINSON CONTACTED SMITH AND OBTAINED DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT.  ROBINSON THEN CONTACTED MR. CHRIS FRILOUX, TRANSPORTATION SPECIALIST FOR AMERICAN CYANAMID.  ROBINSON RELATED ALL OF THE DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT TO FRILOUX. FRILOUX ADVISED THAT HE WOULD FOLLOW UP AGGRESSIVELY WITH HIS PLANTS PERSONNEL RESPONSIBLE FOR TANK CAR SECUREMENT.

PACKAGE WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING.  EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED THAT THE PLASTIC BOTTLE(S) HAD A RUPTURED SEAM THAT ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  CARTON WAS WET BUT OTHERWISE UNDAMAGED.  PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column14: STORAGE AREA OF F STATE RT 22
column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: VII & VIII ABOVE: NO PACKAGING FAILURE INVOLVED.  THIS INCIDENT WAS THE RESULT OF THE OVERFILL OF AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK.  OUR DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO PICK UP A LOAD OF UNLEADED GASOLINE FOR PORT HENRY OIL COMPANY.  INSTEAD, HE LOADED A LOAD OF #2 FUEL OIL.  THE CUSTOMER'S #2 FUEL STORAGE TANK DID NOT HAVE ROOM FOR A WHOLE LOAD OF OIL AND ABOUT 580 GALLONS OF OIL CAME OUT THE TOP VENT PIPE BEFORE OUR DRIVER NOTICED IT. (IT WAS 1:00AM).  THE OIL THAT SPILLED WAS CONTAINED IN THE DIKED AREA SURROUNDING THE TANKS AND NO ENVIROMENTAL DAMAGE RESULTED.  THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMELTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND THEIR OFFICALS SUPERVISED THE CLEANUP N.Y.S. D.E.C. REFERENCE NUMBER FOR THIS INCIDENT IS 9307627.  THE HIGH COST OF CLEANUP IS MOSTLY ATTRIBUTED TO THE LABOR INVOLVED IN REMOVING THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL UNDER THE TANKS. OUR DRIVER FAILED TO READ THE GAUGES AS WELL AS DELIVERING THE WRONG PRODUCT.  HE WAS SUSPENDED FOR TWO WEEKS IN ACCORDANCE WITH HIS UNION CONTRACT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: LOOSE CAP. 2 CUPS LEAKED.  ALCOHOL EVAPORATED RAPIDLY.  THE SHIPPER DID NOT SECURE THE CAPS PROPERLY.  CAPS MUST BE TIGHT AND TAPED.  PACKAGE WAS FOUND WET, BROUGHT TO DAMAGE REWWRAP ARE.  CAPS WERE TIGHTENED AND SECURED AND RETURNED IN A NEW BOX.  THERE WAS NO UNABSORBED LIQUID PRESENT.
PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING.  SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED AND BALANCE OF UNDAMAGED MATERIAL RETURNED.  DAMAGED PORTION DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

THE HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO A POSSIBLE HAZMAT SPILL.  1 BOX OF 14 HAD FALLEN FROM A HUT AND WAS CRUSHED BY A FORKLIFT.  THE MATERIAL WAS IDENTIFIED AS COSTMETICS, N.O.S.  THE SHIPMENT WAS CLEANED UP, CONTAINERIZED AND PLACED IN THE DISPOSAL AREA, AWAITING DISPOSITION BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT.

HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED AT 0455L OF A POSSIBLE HAZMAT SPILL AT D-2. SHIPMENT WAS IDENTIFIED AS COSMETICS, N.O.S. 4 PIECES OF 20 FELL HUT AND WERE CRUSHED BY A FORKLIFT. SHIPMENT WAS CLEANED UP, CONTAINERIZED AND PLACED IN THE DISPOSAL AREA, AWAITING DISPOSTION BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT.

AT APPROX. 1030 HOURS ON SEPT. 12TH AT CONWAY YARD, TANK CAR GATX 50132 WAS HUMPED.  AS THE CAR WAS ROLLING THROUGH CROSSOVERS, TWO HUMP MAINTAINERS NOTICED PRODUCT ON THE TOP AND SIDE OF THE CAR.  MECHANICAL FORCES FOUND A RUPTURED 100# FLANGIBLE DISC.  BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES SENIOR INSPECTOR T.J. MANNAS REPLACED THE DISC AND THE CAR WAS RELASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

PVS-NOLWOOD CHEMICALS, INC. DRIVER, BOB ADAMS, ARRIVED AT CADON PLATING, 3715 11TH ST, WYANDOTTE, AT APPROXIMATELY 12:45 PM ON MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 13, 1993, TO DELIVER A 7000 GALLON LOAD OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  THE STATIONARY STORAGE TANK HAS A CAPACITY OF AT LEAST 12,000 GALLONS, HAS A TANK GAUGE, IS DIKED WITH A CONCRETE CONTAINMENT, AND HAD A HIGH LEVEL ALARM WHICH IS RIGGERED AT 10,000 GALLONS.  THE DRIVER, AS REQUIRED BY SOP, CHECKED IN WITH CADON SUPERVISORY PERSONNEL, WHO SHOWED HIM WHERE TO HOOK UP AND ASSURED HIM THAT THE TANK WOULD HOLD THE LOAD.  THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO HOOK UP THE TANK TRUCK AND UNLOAD THE HC1.  DURING THE UNLAODING PROCESS, THE STATIONARY TANK OVERFLOWEED APPROXIMATLEY 200 - 300 GALLONS THROUGH THE OVERFLOW DRAIN INTO THE DIKED AREA.  THE DKIE HAD A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM PART OF THE CONCRETE BLOCK WALL, SO THE HC1 FLOWED OUT OF THE CONTAINMENT AREA AND ONTO AN ADJACENT CONCRETE PAD.  THE DRIVER WAS NOT AWARE OF THE SPILL IMMEDIATELY BECAUSE, STATIONED "IN ATTENDANCE" AT THE BACK OF HIS TRUCK, THE DIKE WALL BLOCKED HIS VIEW OF IT.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH SODA ASH, NEUTRALIZED, AND DISPOSED OF BY THE CUSTOMER. THERE WERE NO INJURIES. THE INCIDENT WAS FINISHED BY 3:30 PM.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings; Vent
column168: ON SEPTEMBER 18,1993, AT APPROXIMATELY 0600 HOURS, SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, DEAN WOMACK WAS CONTACTED BY YARDMASTER, STEVE JORDON.  MR JORDON INFORMED WOMACK THAT TANK CAR GATX 21407, WHICH CONTAINED SULFURIC ACID, WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  MR JORDON FURTHER STATED THAT SWITCHMAN ROBERT GOINS (439-11-3097) HAD A SMALL AMOUNT OF THIS PRODUCT MAKE CONTACT WITH THE SKIN ON HIS NECK BUT REFUSED MEDICAL TREATMENT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0640 HOURS, WOMACK ARRIVED AT REISOR YARD AND FOUND THIS CAR BLUE FLAGGED IN TRACK SIX.  WOMACK INSPECTED THE CAR AND DISCOVERED THAT THE 100 POUND CDC FRANGIBLE DISC AND SECURED CAR.  SGT. BOBBITT OF THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE REQUESTED THAT THE SPILLAGE ON THE CAR AND GROUND BE NEUTRALIZED. WOMACK USED POTASH THAT WAS SUPPLIED BY AGENT MIKE DEER OF THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY TO COMPLY WITH SGT BOBBITTS REQUEST. THE CAR WAS THEN WASHED WITH WATER BY THE DISTRICT 3 FIRE DEPARMENT.  GATX 21403 WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 0930 HOURS. CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER, BILL LEE WERE INFORMED OF THIS INCIDENT.  MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS, LARRY ERWIN, INTERVIEW ROBERT GOINS, WHO REFUSED TO CLAIM THIS EXPOSURE AS AN INJURY.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0135 HRS. ON 09/01/93 SPECIAL AGENT T.J. BOUDREAX RECEIVED INFORMATION FROM SPECIAL AGNET T.S CARMICHAEL WHO ADVISED THAT A SLIGH LEAK WAS DETECTED ON A TANK CAR APPROXIMATELY 15 CARS FROM THE REAR END OF RUN THRU TRIN NS #315.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0155 HRS.  BOUDREAUX LOCATED TANK CAR RAIX 2708 WHICH HAD A SLIGHT LEAK.  LOOSE PLUGS WERE FOUND ON 1 LIQUID VALVE AND 1 AIR INDUCTION VALVE. ALSO 8 OF 8 MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE FOUND LOOSE.  ALL PLUGS AND MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  AT 0305 HRS. column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY DON ERTLE, SUPERVISOR YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, THAT TANK CAR GATX 98134 WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR WHILE BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL YARD SWITCHING OPERATIONS. column168: ON 09/21/93 AT APPROX 9:00AM, WHILE INSPECTING INTERCHANGE CARS FROM UP, NOLR FOUND PPGX 3179 ON INTERCHANGE TRACK IN GOULDSBORO, LA YARD (UP) TO HAVE A SMALL DRIP LEAK FROM BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. CAR INSPECTED BY RESCAR (CAR REPAIR CONTRACTOR) WHO TRIED TO IMMEDIATELY STOP LEAK BY TIGHTENING BOLTS, ETC. NOT ABLE TO ACCOMPLISH SO CHEVRON WAS CONTACTED AS WELL AS UNION PACIFIC MTO ADVISED.  AT APPROX. 10:30 AM VARIOUS REPRESENTATIVES FROM NOLR, RESCAR, UP, CHEVRON AND LA STATE HAZ MATERIAL UNIT. AFTER ASSESSING  MINOR LEAK AND MAKING TEMPORARY REPAIRS TO CATCH DRIP, STATE HWY TROOPER ROBERT PINERO AUTHORIZED CAR TO BE MOVED INTO PLANT FOR ALL LOADING SINCE NECESSARY REPAIRS COULD NOT BE MADE WHILE UNLOADED. CAR BAD ORDERED AND BEING RETURNED TO HOME SHOP ON 9/24/93. THE FOLLOWING ARE FROM 93100372 SPECIAL AGENT BOUDREAUX WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANK CAR PPGX 3179 ON TRACK #48 IN THE GOULDSBORO YARD, GRETNA, LA. WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.  AGENT BOUDREAUX INSPECTED TANK CAR AND NOTED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 6 DROPS PER MINUTE.  ATTEMPTS TO CLOSE THE VALVE BY CLOSING THE TOP OPERATING LEVER ONE HALF TURN MET WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS.  REG. MGR. POLICE, P.A. MILLER AND LOUISIANA STATE POLICE TROOPER, BOB PINERO ARRIVED AND ASSISTED BY SECURING A PLASTIC BUCKET TO CATCH THE LEAKING PRODUCT.  AGENT BOUDREAUX ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET AUXILIARY VALVE PLUG AND DISCOVERED THAT THE PLUG HAS APPARENTLY DETERIORATED TO THE POINT THAT IT DID NOT SECURE THE LEAK. MARK WANLESS OF RESCAR INC., A CONTRACTOR FOR NEW ORLEANS LOWER COAST RR, ARRIVED AND CONTACTED CHEVRON CHEMICAL.  CHEVRON REQUESTED THAT THE TANK CAR BE MOVED TO THEIR PLANT, 5 MILES SOUTH OF GOULDSBORO YARD, AFTER THE LEAK WAS SECURED.  AGENT BOUDREAUX & TROOPER PINERO SECURED THE LEAK BY TAPING A RUBBER GLOVE, THEN A POLYETHELENE BAG, OVER THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO CATCH LEAKING PRODUCT WHILE ENROUTE TO THE CHEVRON CHEMICAL PLANT.  TANK CAR WSA MOVED TO THE CHEVRON PLANT WITHOUT INCIDENT.  AGENT BOUDREAUX NOTIFIED CHEVRON CHEMICAL SUPERVISOR GAUTIER AND CHEMTREC'S BILL GASSON OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: LEAK WAS DISCOVERED AT JACKSON. OPENED TRAILER COULD NOT FIND WHAT WAS LEAKING, SO WE MOVED ALL FREIGHT TO AN EMPTY TRAILER. FOUND AN ORDER FOR 24 DRUMS NOSED IN TRAILER AND LEAKING. THEY CALLED AROUND 8:30 A.M. AND SAID THEY WOULD SEND A CLEAN UP CREW IN A COUPLE OF HOURS. THE CREW ARRIVED AROUND NOON. MOVED ALL DRUMS TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND FOUND ONE LEAKING. THEY THEN PUT IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. WE RECEIVED INSTRUCTIONS TO SEND RECOVERY DRUM TO: DOW CHEMICAL USA TEXAS OPERATION ATTN: TED KASPER BRAZOPORT AVENUE BLDG B-6405 FREEPORT TEXAS 77541.

ON SEPTEMBER 17, 1993, I, BEN TAYLOR, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DR., WILMINGTON OHIO 45177, RECEIVED A CALL OVER THE RADIO THAT A PACKAGE LABELED FLAMMABLE LIQUID FELL OUT OF A LOAD DEVICE TYPE CONTAINER ONTO A CONCRETE FLOOR AND UPON IMPACT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING, AND IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT WHATEVER WAS LEAKING HAD A STRONG ODOR.  I ASKED IF THERE WERE ANY IGNITION SOURCES NEAR THE VICINITY OF THE LEAKING PACKAGE AND THIS WAS ACKNOWLEDGE WITH AN AFFIRMATIVE RESPONSE.  I THEN ADVISED THAT THIS SOURCE BE SHUT OFF TO ELIMINATE ANY CHANCE FOR A FIRE OR EXPLOSION.  I IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED A P/T SPILL TECHNICIAN TO THE AREA TO ASSESS THE SCENE AND DETERMINE WHAT NEEDED TO BE DONE TO MITIGATE THE SITUATION.  UPON ARRIVAL, SPILL TECHNICIAN DON FLOREA ADVISED THAT THE PACKAGE CONTAINED TOLUENE, AND THAT VERY LITTLE APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED FROM THE PACKAGE AT THIS TIME.  THE PACKAGE WAS QUICKLY PLACED IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS AND TRANSPORTED TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT FACILITY FOR CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE.  AGENT JOEL SCHAEFER OF THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINSTRATION OF THE COLUMBUS OHIO, CASFU OFFICE WAS HERE DOING SOME OTHER WORK AT THE TIME AND I ASKED IF HE WOULD TAKE A LOOK AT THIS PACKAGE WITH ME.  AT THIS TIME THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED IN AGENT SCHAEFER'S PRESENCE AND IT WAS FOUND THAT THE PACKAGE CONTAINED 2 x 1 QUART GLASS BOTTLES IN INDIVIDUAL INNER CARDBOARD BOXES, ONE OF WHICH WAS COMPLETELY DESTROYED APPARENTLY DUE TO THE IMPACT IT HAD WITH THE CONCRETE FLOOR WHEN THE PACKAGE FELL OUT OF THE LOAD DEVICE TYPE CONTAINER.  THE PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED, CERTIFIED, AND APPEARED FROM THE OUTSIDE TO BE IN COMPLIANCE WITH THE CODE OF FEDERAL REGULATIONS, TITLE 49.  THE PACKAGE HAD AMPLE ABSORBENT AND CUSHIONING MATERIAL (VERMICULITE), BUT WHAT IS BELIEVED TO BE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR TO WHY ONE OF THE INNER GLASS BOTTLES BREAKING WAS THE FACT THAT THEY WERE IMPROPERLY PLACED INSIDE OF THE PACKAGE.  I.E. THE INNER CARDBOARD BOXES, DIMS APPROX. 3 1/2" x 3 1/2" x 8" WERE SET INTO THE OUTER PACKAGE FLAT ON THE BOTTOM AND FLAT AGAINST THE INNER MOST SIDE OF THE PACKAGE, THUS NOT ALLOWING THE VERMICULITE TO SEPERATE THESE INNER MOST PACKAGES FROM THE OUTER PACKING.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT THERE WAS AT LEAST 1" - 1 1/2" OF ROOM FOR THE VERMICULITE TO BE PLACED UNDER THE INNER PACKAGE AND THE BOTTOM OF THE OUTER PACKAGE AS WELL ON THE SIDES.  THE PACKAGE AS STATED EARLIER DID HAVE ALL THE PROPER INNER, OUTER MATERIALS, BUT WHAT ATTRIBUTED TO THE FAILURE OF ONE, OF THE INNER GLASS BOTTLES WAS HOW IT WAS PLACED INSIDE THE PACKAGE PRIOR TO SHIPPING.  AGENT JOEL SCHAEFER, WHILE VISUALLY INSPECTING THIS SHIPMENT, TOOK PICTURES OF BOTH THE INNER AND OUTER PACKAGING PRIOR TO AND AFTER OENING THE SHIPMENT TO AS CERTAIN WHAT MAY HAVE ATTRIBUTED TO THE LEAK AFTER FALLING APPROXIMATELY FOUR FEET ONTO A FLAT CONCRETE SURFACE.   UPON COMPLETION OF THE VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE INNER AND OUTER PACKAGING, THIS PACKAGE WAS PLAC

DANGEROUS GOODS WAS CALLED TO S18R1 TO CHECK LEAKING PACKAGE.  UPON ARRIVAL THE DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST FOUND A COURIER PAK BOX WITH A STAIN ON ONE SIDE WITH AN ODOR OF PAINT REMOVER OR THINNER.  THEY PROCEEDED TO OPEN THE PACKAGE AND FOUND A ONE QUART METAL CAN OF MUTIPLE MARKING REMOVER CONTAINING TOLUOL, ACETONE, AND PETROLEUM DISTILLATES. THE CAN WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP BECAUSE THE CAP HAD CAME LOOSE DURING TRANSIT.  THE WORDS FLAMMABLE, KEEP AWAY FROM FIRE WERE PRINTED ON THE CAN.  COPY OF MSDS IS ATTACHED.

THE DRIVER ARRRIVED AT THE BULK PLANT AT APPROXIMATELY 9:55a.m.  NO ONE WAS IN THE OFFICE OF THE PLANT, BUT, BOTH GATES WERE OPEN.  THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD 6,500 GALLONS OF NO-LEAD GASOLINE INTO THE PROPER TANK AND THEN WHEN THIS WAS COMPLETED, HE PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD 1,500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL INTO THE TANK THAT WAS MARKED FOR DIESEL FUEL.  THE DRIVER WAS NOT AWARE THAT THIS TANK WAS FULL AND AS HE PUMPED THE DIESEL FUEL INTO THE FILL PIPE, APPROXIMATELY 870 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL SPILLED OUT OF THE STAND PIPE IN THE TANK AND OVERFLOWED INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE DRIVER DID NOT NOTICE THIS OVERFLOW OR SPILLAGE BECAUSE THE TANKER WAS BETWEEN HIM AND THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  HAD THE FILL PIPES BEEN MARKED CORRECTLY, THIS SPILL MAY NOT HAVE OCCURED.  THE DRIVER DID NOT KNOW THAT ANOTHER TANK HAD BEEN DESIGNATED FOR DIESEL FUEL AND THAT THAT SHOULD HAVE BEEN THE TANK HE WAS TO UNLOAD INTO.  THE SPILL PIPES WERE MISMARKED AND ACTUALLY HE SHOULD HAVE UNLOADED THE 1,500 GALLONS INTO THE FILL PIPE MARKED WHITE, FOR NO-LEAD GAS, BUT, HE HAD NO WAY OF KNOWING THIS.  THE DRIVER WAS FAMILIAR WITH THE ASHLAND OIL COLOR CODES AND ALSO THE API CODE WHICH IS WHAT HE USED,  THE FOLLOWING AGENCES WERE NOTIFIED: KY STATE FIRE MARSHAL, D.E.S. AND THE N.R.C. MIKE MCCURRY RESPONDED WITH THE SPILL TRAILER AND RECOVERED 520 GALLONS.  GORDON PHILLIPS EXCAVATING OF LEXINGTON, KY ASSISTED IN THE CLEAN-UP.  THE EPA AND WATER QUALITY WAS NOTIFIED AND CAME OUT AND INSPECTED THE AREA.  THEY SAID THEY DIDN'T HAVE ANY PROBLEMS AND WE WERE TOLD TO CLEAN THE SPILL TO ASHLAND OILS CRITERIA AND COMMUNICATE WITH WASTE MANAGEMENT ON THE LOCATION TO TAKE THE CONTAIMINATED SOIL.  WE ARE CURRENTLY REINFORCING OUT POLICY TO RESTRAIN FROM UNLOADING PRODUCT UNTIL THERE ARE ATTENDENTS AT THE UNLOADING SITE.

column168: PACKAGE FELL OFF A SLIDE AND HIT THE GRATING, CREATING A GAS LEAK FROM THE PACKAGE.  THE GAS WAS VERY STRONG AND, AS A RESULT, THE GRAY BELT AND SURROUNDING AREAS WERE EVACUATED. MEANWHILE, WE MOVED THE TRAILERS OFF THE DOORS - BOTH FOR THEIR PROTECTION AND FOR BETTER VENTILATION.  WE SHUT THE ENTIRE BUILDING DOWN AT THIS POINT.
